Subject: [sfraves] NRR: A joke to brighten your day.

------=_Part_4970_8746611.1209666919528
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

Guy's in the hospital, goes into surgery and wakes up the next day with the
surgeon in his room.

Surgeon says to the guy, "Sir, I've got some good news and some bad news.
Which would you like to hear first?"

Guy says, "Give me the bad news first doc, that way the good news'll soften
the blow afterwards."

Surgeon says, "Okay sir, while you were in surgery we had to amputate both
of your legs."

Guy says, "JESUS DOC! WHAT THE FUCK KINDA GOOD NEWS IS GONNA MAKE ME FEEL
BETTER AFTER THAT!?!?!"

Surgeon cracks a smile and says, "The guy in the next bed wants to buy your
shoes."

------=_Part_4970_8746611.1209666919528--

PS That joke should end with something about the guy's Johnson being intact and not his neighbor wanting his shoes.  Comedy 101,  the Johnson is always funny.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: How Weird Afterparty @ Supperclub Sunday - The Fingermonsters Live!!!

Calling all weirdos, freaks, and strange brews!  How Weird is back again
this year, giving you another excuse to party in the streets.  Supperclub
and Rock It Science are teaming up to bring you an afterparty just 2 blocks
from the fair in one of SF's premier venues with visionary musical selectors
and live performances.  LowPro Lounge emerges from the underground to host
La Salle Prive.  Get your faux fur, weird wigs, hats, and general absurdity
on and join us for an evening of debauchery!

Sunday, May 4th 2008 6 PM - 2 AM

Supperclub: 657 Harrison Street @ 3rd, SF

Rock It Science & Supperclub SF Present

Weird Science: A How Weird After-Soiree

Featuring 2 rooms of live & DJ'ed electronic music

Food Plates available (Veggie & Vegan friendly)

$5 in Weird Outfit

For dinner reservations call 415 348 0800 or visit www.supperclub.com

La Salle Neige:

The Fingermonsters Live (myspace.com/fingermonsters)

The Fingermonsters create maximal floor-magnet tracks with tongue firmly in
cheek and hands firmly on knobs.  They've been tearing San Francisco and the
Bay Area a new one with a 4-person live laptop/drum machine PA assault that
is not to be missed. Check out their releases on Monsta Music if you dare!


MC Souleye & Dylan Cahill of Blvd Live (blvdsource.com)

Bridging gaps between hip hop, drum & bass, electronica and funk, Souleye
has emerged as one of the most sought-after MCs in the live music and dance
club scenes.
Dylan Cahill was raised in SF and has been active in the Bay Area music
scene for the last 12 years drumming, DJing and producing music. 
Hip-Hop, Electro, and Breaks with live MCing: in other words expect the
unexpected from this duo!


Late Night Sneaky Live (Supperclub)

Live house music at its finest from SF staple Late Night Sneaky.  Decks,
guitars, and general madness!


Eric Sharp (myspace.com/ericsharp)

Rock It Science founder and local hero Eric Sharp will drop a signature
eclectic, weird dj set.


Friction (Purgatory Cruiser, Yno5 - myspace.com/friction001)

Friction is one of the best DJ's in Northern California, dropping bass
throbbing breaks & Electrohouse.  You're gonna hear a lot more from this
rising star.


Native Intelligence (Rock It Science)

B Smiley (Supperclub)


La Salle Prive hosted by Lowpro Lounge

Majitope
Citizen 10
Bender
Roja

----- Original Message ----
From: Andrew Phelan <mailinglists@djandrewphelan.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Thursday, May 1, 2008 12:48:57 PM
Subject: [sfraves] BSP: How Weird Afterparty @ Supperclub Sunday - The Fingermonsters Live!!!

Calling all weirdos, freaks, and strange brews!  How Weird is back again
this year, giving you another excuse to party in the streets.  Supperclub
and Rock It Science are teaming up to bring you an afterparty just 2 blocks
from the fair in one of SF's premier venues with visionary musical selectors
and live performances.  LowPro Lounge emerges from the underground to host
La Salle Prive.  Get your faux fur, weird wigs, hats, and general absurdity
on and join us for an evening of debauchery!

Sunday, May 4th 2008 6 PM - 2 AM

Supperclub: 657 Harrison Street @ 3rd, SF

Rock It Science & Supperclub SF Present

Weird Science: A How Weird After-Soiree

Featuring 2 rooms of live & DJ'ed electronic music

Food Plates available (Veggie & Vegan friendly)

$5 in Weird Outfit

For dinner reservations call 415 348 0800 or visit www.supperclub.com

La Salle Neige:

The Fingermonsters Live (myspace.com/fingermonsters)

The Fingermonsters create maximal floor-magnet tracks with tongue firmly in
cheek and hands firmly on knobs.  They've been tearing San Francisco and the
Bay Area a new one with a 4-person live laptop/drum machine PA assault that
is not to be missed. Check out their releases on Monsta Music if you dare!


MC Souleye & Dylan Cahill of Blvd Live (blvdsource.com)

Bridging gaps between hip hop, drum & bass, electronica and funk, Souleye
has emerged as one of the most sought-after MCs in the live music and dance
club scenes.
Dylan Cahill was raised in SF and has been active in the Bay Area music
scene for the last 12 years drumming, DJing and producing music. 
Hip-Hop, Electro, and Breaks with live MCing: in other words expect the
unexpected from this duo!


Late Night Sneaky Live (Supperclub)

Live house music at its finest from SF staple Late Night Sneaky.  Decks,
guitars, and general madness!


Eric Sharp (myspace.com/ericsharp)

Rock It Science founder and local hero Eric Sharp will drop a signature
eclectic, weird dj set.


Friction (Purgatory Cruiser, Yno5 - myspace.com/friction001)

Friction is one of the best DJ's in Northern California, dropping bass
throbbing breaks & Electrohouse.  You're gonna hear a lot more from this
rising star.


Native Intelligence (Rock It Science)

B Smiley (Supperclub)


La Salle Prive hosted by Lowpro Lounge

Majitope
Citizen 10
Bender
Roja

Subject: [sfraves] How we pay our taxes

--0-1965087289-1209709057=:96892
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Suppose that every day, ten men go out for beer and the bill for all ten comes to $100. If they paid their bill the way we pay our taxes, it would go something like this:

The first four men (the poorest) would pay nothing.
The fifth would pay $1.
The sixth would pay $3.
The seventh would pay $7.
The eighth would pay $12.
The ninth would pay $18.
The tenth man (the richest) would pay $59.

So, that's what they decided to do.

The ten men drank in the bar every day and seemed quite happy with the arrangement, until one day, the owner threw them a curve. 'Since you are all such good customers,' he said,

'I'm going to reduce the cost of your daily beer by $20. Drinks for the ten now cost just $80.'

The group still wanted to pay their bill the way we pay our taxes so the first four men were unaffected.

They would still drink for free. But what about the other six men, the paying customers?

How could they divide the $20 windfall so that everyone would get his 'fair share?'

They realized that $20 divided by six is $3.33. But if they subtracted that from everybody's share, then the fifth man and the sixth man would each end up being paid to drink his beer. So, the bar owner suggested that it would be fair to reduce each man's bill by roughly the same amount, and he proceeded to work out the amounts each should pay.

And so:
The fifth man, like the first four, now paid nothing (100% savings).
The sixth now paid $2 instead of $3 (33%savings).
The seventh now paid $5 instead of $7 (28%savings).

The eighth now paid $9 instead of $12 (25% savings).
The ninth now paid $14 instead of $18 (22% savings).
The tenth now paid $49 instead of $59 (16% savings).

Each of the six was better off than before. And the first four continued to drink for free. But once outside the restaurant, the men began to compare their savings.

I only got a dollar out of the $20,'declared the sixth man. He pointed to the tenth man,' but he got $10!' 'Yeah, that's right,' exclaimed the fifth man. 'I only saved a dollar, too. It's unfair that he got ten times more than I!' 'That's true!!' shouted the seventh man. 'Why should he get $10 back when I got only two? The wealthy get all the breaks!' 'Wait a minute,' yelled the first four men in unison. 'We didn't get anything at all. The system exploits the poor!'

The nine men surrounded the tenth and beat him up. The next night the tenth man didn't show up for drinks, so the nine sat down and had beers without him. But when it came time to pay the bill, they discovered something important. They didn't have enough money between all of them for even half of the bill!

And that, ladies and gentlemen, journalists and college professors, is how our tax system works. The people who pay the highest taxes get the most benefit from a tax reduction. Tax them too much, attack them for being wealthy, and they just may not show up anymore. In fact, they might start drinking overseas where the atmosphere is somewhat friendlier.

David R. Kamerschen, Ph.D.
Professor of Economics
University of Georgia

For those who understand, no explanation is needed.
For those who do not understand, no explanation is possible.


--0-1965087289-1209709057=:96892--

I say this is pure bullshit.

The rich man has the means to invest and to diversify. The first four 
don't because they do not have the means of even paying for their beer.
The hardest part for many is getting the first million, after that it is 
pure simplicity to multiply that from all of the tax benefits and 
shelters given with only a minimal of research. Nice try in trying to 
prove in a round about way that the rich man that has it rough, though.

I run my own company. I know firsthand the benefits given for simple 
shit that the poor people have absolutely no access to.

-t

Subject: Re: [sfraves] How we pay our taxes

--0-1781036030-1209720932=:20805
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Something someone posted to another list (from elsewhere):
   
  (Note that I didn't write this, nor did David Kamerschen Ph.D write the other. Its just internet BS the likes of which have been forwarded back and forth for about the last five or six years.)
  

    In the US and throughout most of the rest of the world, the tenth man would have paid off a politician for $10 to get a beer subsidy of $30 per night(to create jobs for the bartender). Of this $30, $10 of course would have covered the lobbying expense, $10 would go in his own pocket, $1 would go to the bartender to keep his mouth shut, and $9 would go to the bar.
  

  The Bar would give him a kickback of $10 each night for bringing in his 9 buddies to make them into alcoholics, repeat customers for life.
  

  The Bar would then raise their prices to $130 citing inflation and higher taxes.
  

  The tenth richest man would then secure his finances in a Dutch Holding Company managed by a trust in Ireland which invests in Chase and Bank of America. He would then explain to his buddies that he is as poor as the rest of them and cant afford to pay himself as he cries into his beer that night citing his latest financial report which shows him to be broke on paper so that he doesnt have to pay taxes in the United States ever again.
  

  Citing his former generosity, the other nine men would agree that the tenth man can now pay nothing like the 4 poorest.
  

  The others would then be faced with an adjusted amount of
  

      * The fifth would pay $3.
      * The sixth would pay $10.
      * The seventh would pay $22.
      * The eighth would pay $38.
      * The ninth would pay $57.
  

  Now the group would recognize that this is not fair and so would lobby the Government for an Earned Drinking Credit for the Poorest men. The government would oblige and give the four poorest men $2 each, but they would tax the 5th - 9th men $2 each as well.
  

      * 4 men receive a total of $8 and 5 men pay $10.
  

  The adjusted amounts would then look like this for all 10
  

      * First Receives $2 pays $2 | Net 0
      * Second Receives $2 pays $2 | Net 0
      * Third Receives $2 pays $2 | Net 0
      * Fourth Receives $2 pays $2 | Net 0
      * Fifth Pay $1 to bar pays $2 to tax | net paid $3
      * Sixth Pay $8 to bar; pays $2 to tax | net paid $10
      * Seventh Pay $20 to bar; pays $2 to tax | net paid $22
      * Eighth Pay $36 to bar pays $2 to tax | net paid $38
      * Ninth Pay $55 to bar; pays $2 to tax | net paid $57
      * Tenth Man:  Tax Credit Received: $30 ;
        Pays $10 to politician;
        $1 to bartender;
        Receives $10 from Bar
        Net RECEIVED $29 per night and free beer
  

  Of course this can not go on forever as the sixth, seventh, eighth and ninth men cant afford to pay those rates forever. So they start paying with their credit cards held by Bank of America and Chase.
  

  The tenth man would start demanding a higher Return on Investment from his investment managers, who would be hearing similar requests from all of their other investors. They would then expand their holdings into mortgaged back securities where a good deal more profit could be made.
  

  Meanwhile the Fifth through ninth men are racking up debt on their credit cards from drinking every night, their health care costs are increasing as their liver fails, and they are also spending more on gasoline as they drink and drive as they can no longer afford to cab it.
  

  Ultimately, they end up refinancing their credit cards into their house where they have equity. The mortgage broker promises them a 4.9% interest rate on the refinance which sounds good as their credit card interest rate is up to 21%. The broker promises them that they will not have to verify their income, provide W2s nor copies of their tax paper work.
  

  Their mortgage broker doesnt tell them, but lies about the value of their house in order to refinance their credit and help them avoid paying private mortgage insurance. At their current income levels, and without verifying their income, their mortgage would be classified as Sub Prime and the interest rate would be 10.9%
  

  The mortgage officer lies about their income levels as well to boost the internal credit scoring mechanism and get them financed, not at 4.9% but 5.9%, which is better than 10.9% and happens to pay the mortgage broker a higher commission than a loan at 4.9% that is not sub prime.
  

  The mortgage broker also promises them a payment of $900 per month, but fails to mention the balloon payment of $50,000 in the 5th year and doesnt mention the adjustable rates in year 3.
  

  The men separately show up with a hangover and sun glasses on the date of their close for their new mortgages. They trust their broker and do not read the paperwork in detail flipping and signing almost as fast as they could raise a beer bottle to their lips.
  

  The loan closes, the mortgage broker gets a fat commission, the bank securitizes the mortgages by selling them to a Hedge Fund and pockets collectively a billion dollars in profits that year.
  

  The hedge fund holds the investment for a year, shows a 35% gain on paper and starts selling shares to retirement funds and 401ks in the US that the Sixth through 9th men just happen to have the rest of their life savings sitting in.
  

  The tenth man sees the writing on the wall, literally magic marker on a stall in the restroom of the bar.
  

  The end is Nigh
  

  He pulls his money out of the Hedge fund invested in real estate and invests in Gold at $600 a troy ounce.
  

  Meanwhile, he lobbies congress to tighten bankruptcy laws for credit cards which he still has a sizable investment in. Congress tightens bankruptcy laws and makes it impossible to absolve credit card debt, forcing people into chapter 13 where they must pay off the debt within 3 years.
  

  Gas prices are still going up so the President ignores a minor terrorist threat, allows the terrorists to blow up a major building and then goes to war with the terrorists home country where there is no oil, and simultaneously with a country that sits on 10% of the worlds oil reserves that has a decimated military infrastructure.
  

  Oil prices shoot through the roof with Gold following close behind. The President whose family comes from oil barons make a fortune and become famous at their skull and bones country club outside of Yale.
  

  Meanwhile our famous 10 guys, start paying even more money at the pump. The first 4 guys end up taking second jobs working at Wal-Mart and have to give up drinking at the bar so that they can try and beat their teenage kids out of a promotion.
  

  The fifth and sixth guys get foreclosed upon. They were forced to stop paying their mortgage payments so that they could pay their mandatory credit card payments as required by the new bankruptcy law.
  

  The seventh, eighth and ninth men all previously traded up their homes for McMansions that they can not afford with interest only payments of $2300 a month. When foreclosures start happening their plans on flipping their McMansions and cashing in on the equity slips through their fingers.
  

  To make matters worse seven and eight get laid off from the companies they work for when their jobs get outsourced to China. The ninth man keeps his job at a law firm, but fails to notice that his 401k fund is slipping and has lost 10% in the last year. Things are looking up as his law firm seems on the edge of landing a big contract with Merrill Lynch.
  

  Then the real estate crash and sub prime mortgage scandal erupt. Banks start dropping like flies to be saved not by the cash strapped government that can barely afford the war for oil any longer, but by China. Oil and Gold soar, Gold hits $900 a troy ounce and Oil hits $130 a barrel (about the same amount for 10 rounds of beer prior to the crash). Beer prices hold steady for the first few months, but then start to edge up as gas prices for delivery creep into the bar owners expenses.
  

  Then the first four men one night remember their favorite bar. They sneak around back around 4:30 am and steal 50 empty kegs that just happen to be made of pure aluminum. Those kegs are now worth about half the value of a keg that is full in scrap metal prices or about $80.
  

  They are not stupid and dont want to get caught turning the kegs in at the dump where the police are already looking for keg thieves. So they head out to the closed down manufacturing plant where they used to work. They start a big fire, and melt down the aluminum into big messy aluminum splashes on the cement.
  

  They turn in the aluminum for cash and get caught up on their back alimony and child support before heading back to work at Wal-mart where they now work for their teen age kids that beat them out for that promotion earlier in the month because their job skills werent as good as recent high school graduates.  They then begin dreaming of new ways to find aluminum alimony allowances.
  

  Meanwhile, the banks and mortgage companies lobby congress spending about $10,000 a head in an election year to bail out the economy. Congress provides the major banks with government backed loans to refinance the bad sub prime loans so that the government can personally guarantee those bad loans. They also put $100 billion of actual cash into the hands of Americans hoping to stimulate the economy.
  

  Americans however, are all in debt up to their eye balls and use the extra $1200 they receive to make 2-3 credit card payments. They take the $300 for each kid and buy groceries for the month and then they start worrying about next month.
  

  The banks get away free as they have Chinese financing now and no bad loans as they have refinanced them over to the US Government. The US government had to print more money to pay for all of these actions and so Gold goes up to $1500 a troy ounce.
  

  The tenth man is now worth Billions and moves to Costa Rica to retire taking the new trophy wife that used to be the bartenders girl friend with him.
  

  The first four men end up going to county prison for 3 months for stealing aluminum dog crap receptacles after running out of kegs to steal.
  

  The fifth and sixth men end up living in an apartment and then homeless after they lose their jobs at Wal-Mart.
  

  The seventh and eighth men whom we previously left hanging in our story after they lost their jobs and ability to pay for their homes, end up losing their homes, and their kids. They and their spouses are each convicted of mortgage fraud by the FBI in a major sting operation after it is revealed that they lied on their mortgage applications. Their mortgage brokers who actually did the paper work cop a plea agreement in exchange for immunity with the Feds and rat out each of their unsuspecting customers.
  

  The ninth man ends up losing his entire retirement fund which took a big hit as the dollar rapidly plummeted into free fall. He ends up refinancing his own house under a government backed loan for $650,000. Unfortunately, a tornado comes through that winter in a freak coincidence and levels the home. FEMA promises to provide assistance but never shows up and the ninth man freezes to death attempting to salvage the shreds of his belongings. His home insurance policy refuses to pay as they claim that his house was over valued and then they prove it with comparables studies from his own mortgage brokers database.
  

  The tenth man ends up dumping his new bride a year later, moving back to the states a year after that when the US appears to have hit rock bottom and he leads a Chinese real estate investment initiative in the states. He makes another $10 billion in ten years, but is then executed in Beijing for espionage.
  


  

tbSMITH <iamgod@dementim.com> wrote:
  I say this is pure bullshit.

The rich man has the means to invest and to diversify. The first four 
don't because they do not have the means of even paying for their beer.
The hardest part for many is getting the first million, after that it is 
pure simplicity to multiply that from all of the tax benefits and 
shelters given with only a minimal of research. Nice try in trying to 
prove in a round about way that the rich man that has it rough, though.

I run my own company. I know firsthand the benefits given for simple 
shit that the poor people have absolutely no access to.

-t

Phillip Mispagel wrote:
> Suppose that every day, ten men go out for beer and the bill for all ten comes to $100. If they paid their bill the way we pay our taxes, it would go something like this:
>
> The first four men (the poorest) would pay nothing.
> The fifth would pay $1.
> The sixth would pay $3.
> The seventh would pay $7.
> The eighth would pay $12.
> The ninth would pay $18.
> The tenth man (the richest) would pay $59.
>
> So, that's what they decided to do.
>
> The ten men drank in the bar every day and seemed quite happy with the arrangement, until one day, the owner threw them a curve. 'Since you are all such good customers,' he said,
>
> 'I'm going to reduce the cost of your daily beer by $20. Drinks for the ten now cost just $80.'
>
> The group still wanted to pay their bill the way we pay our taxes so the first four men were unaffected.
>
> They would still drink for free. But what about the other six men, the paying customers?
>
> How could they divide the $20 windfall so that everyone would get his 'fair share?'
>
> They realized that $20 divided by six is $3.33. But if they subtracted that from everybody's share, then the fifth man and the sixth man would each end up being paid to drink his beer. So, the bar owner suggested that it would be fair to reduce each man's bill by roughly the same amount, and he proceeded to work out the amounts each should pay.
>
> And so:
> The fifth man, like the first four, now paid nothing (100% savings).
> The sixth now paid $2 instead of $3 (33%savings).
> The seventh now paid $5 instead of $7 (28%savings).
>
> The eighth now paid $9 instead of $12 (25% savings).
> The ninth now paid $14 instead of $18 (22% savings).
> The tenth now paid $49 instead of $59 (16% savings).
>
> Each of the six was better off than before. And the first four continued to drink for free. But once outside the restaurant, the men began to compare their savings.
>
> I only got a dollar out of the $20,'declared the sixth man. He pointed to the tenth man,' but he got $10!' 'Yeah, that's right,' exclaimed the fifth man. 'I only saved a dollar, too. It's unfair that he got ten times more than I!' 'That's true!!' shouted the seventh man. 'Why should he get $10 back when I got only two? The wealthy get all the breaks!' 'Wait a minute,' yelled the first four men in unison. 'We didn't get anything at all. The system exploits the poor!'
>
> The nine men surrounded the tenth and beat him up. The next night the tenth man didn't show up for drinks, so the nine sat down and had beers without him. But when it came time to pay the bill, they discovered something important. They didn't have enough money between all of them for even half of the bill!
>
> And that, ladies and gentlemen, journalists and college professors, is how our tax system works. The people who pay the highest taxes get the most benefit from a tax reduction. Tax them too much, attack them for being wealthy, and they just may not show up anymore. In fact, they might start drinking overseas where the atmosphere is somewhat friendlier.
>
> David R. Kamerschen, Ph.D.
> Professor of Economics
> University of Georgia
>
> For those who understand, no explanation is needed.
> For those who do not understand, no explanation is possible.
>
>
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] How we pay our taxes

Not pure bullshit, just a partial truth constructed so as to be believable to those that already believe and almost convincing to those that don't.  The facts as presented are accurate, just not the whole story.  As you point out the ability to invest your money makes a big difference.

And they left out the rest of the story.  After the beating, the tenth
man, in order to get revenge on the other 9, buys the factory where they
all work and fires them.  So the fired men organize a protest which
gets out of hand and the factory is burned to the ground.  Now none of
the men have enough money to buy any food much less drinks, except the rich 10th man who was
(of course) well insured.

He rebuilds the factory, hires 9 different men, and they all start going drinking together every Friday...

Peter

> Phillip Mispagel wrote:
>   
>> Suppose that every day, ten men go out for beer and the bill for all ten comes to $100. If they paid their bill the way we pay our taxes, it would go something like this:
>>
>> The first four men (the poorest) would pay nothing.
>> The fifth would pay $1.
>> The sixth would pay $3.
>> The seventh would pay $7.
>> The eighth would pay $12.
>> The ninth would pay $18.
>> The tenth man (the richest) would pay $59.
>>
>> So, that's what they decided to do.
>>
>> The ten men drank in the bar every day and seemed quite happy with the arrangement, until one day, the owner threw them a curve. 'Since you are all such good customers,' he said,
>>
>> 'I'm going to reduce the cost of your daily beer by $20. Drinks for the ten now cost just $80.'
>>
>> The group still wanted to pay their bill the way we pay our taxes so the first four men were unaffected.
>>
>> They would still drink for free. But what about the other six men, the paying customers?
>>
>> How could they divide the $20 windfall so that everyone would get his 'fair share?'
>>
>> They realized that $20 divided by six is $3.33. But if they subtracted that from everybody's share, then the fifth man and the sixth man would each end up being paid to drink his beer. So, the bar owner suggested that it would be fair to reduce each man's bill by roughly the same amount, and he proceeded to work out the amounts each should pay.
>>
>> And so:
>> The fifth man, like the first four, now paid nothing (100% savings).
>> The sixth now paid $2 instead of $3 (33%savings).
>> The seventh now paid $5 instead of $7 (28%savings).
>>
>> The eighth now paid $9 instead of $12 (25% savings).
>> The ninth now paid $14 instead of $18 (22% savings).
>> The tenth now paid $49 instead of $59 (16% savings).
>>
>> Each of the six was better off than before. And the first four continued to drink for free. But once outside the restaurant, the men began to compare their savings.
>>
>> I only got a dollar out of the $20,'declared the sixth man. He pointed to the tenth man,' but he got $10!' 'Yeah, that's right,' exclaimed the fifth man. 'I only saved a dollar, too. It's unfair that he got ten times more than I!' 'That's true!!' shouted the seventh man. 'Why should he get $10 back when I got only two? The wealthy get all the breaks!' 'Wait a minute,' yelled the first four men in unison. 'We didn't get anything at all. The system exploits the poor!'
>>
>> The nine men surrounded the tenth and beat him up. The next night the tenth man didn't show up for drinks, so the nine sat down and had beers without him. But when it came time to pay the bill, they discovered something important. They didn't have enough money between all of them for even half of the bill!
>>
>> And that, ladies and gentlemen, journalists and college professors, is how our tax system works. The people who pay the highest taxes get the most benefit from a tax reduction. Tax them too much, attack them for being wealthy, and they just may not show up anymore. In fact, they might start drinking overseas where the atmosphere is somewhat friendlier.
>>
>> David R. Kamerschen, Ph.D.
>> Professor of Economics
>> University of Georgia
>>
>> For those who understand, no explanation is needed.
>> For those who do not understand, no explanation is possible.
>>
>>
>>

PS I forgot to mention that the four poorest men are of course charged with the arson, and are unable to afford proper attorneys to defend themselves.  So although they didn't set the fire, they are accused and imprisoned for the crime.  

Naturally the rich tenth man is willing to pay slightly higher taxes to support the punishment and imprisonment of such dangerous criminals, so he does.

The end?

Peter

Not pure bullshit, just a partial truth constructed so as to be believable to those that already believe and almost convincing to those that don't.  The facts as presented are accurate, just not the whole story.  As you point out the ability to invest your money makes a big difference.

And they left out the rest of the story.  After the beating, the tenth
man, in order to get revenge on the other 9, buys the factory where they
all work and fires them.  So the fired men organize a protest which
gets out of hand and the factory is burned to the ground.  Now none of
the men have enough money to buy any food much less drinks, except the rich 10th man who was
(of course) well insured.

He rebuilds the factory, hires 9 different men, and they all start going drinking together every Friday...

Peter

Subject: [sfraves] BSP - Tonight on Radio Integrated :: Disconnect's "Head Cleaner" hard techno mix circa 2000

------=_Part_7962_21989237.1209770154512
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

Tonight on Radio Integrated /// Friday, May 2nd 2008 /// http://radio
.defsf.com:1200/

A classic hard techno mix - DJ Disconnect's "Head Cleaner"

Recorded live on three turntables in 1999/2000, "Head Cleaner" is a great
example of deep, heady, late-90s European techno.  Unless Disconnect gave
you a copy of this tape at a rave in 2001, this is pretty much the only
place you'll hear this mix.  It's on a casette tape even!

Check out the tracklisting and liner notes here:
http://www.defsf.com/people/disconnect

Plus... some modern techno tunes selected by Miss Chelsea Faith


Tune in from 9pm-1am Pacific Time at http://radio.defsf.com:1200/


Love from Chelsea for Radio Integrated

///Radio Integrated :: radiointegrated@gmail.com :: http://radio
.defsf.com:1200/  :: www.myspace.com/radiointegrated

Saturday, May 3rd, 2008

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 1st Saturday at The Endup


featuring from Madrid, Spain:

ALEX UNDER   ** 2 hour live PA **

Plus 8 . Trapez . CMYK Musik . Apnea

The last time Alex Under played for us, his intense aural onslaught
had the Endup crowd going absolutely mental, and prompted
resident Alland Byallo to name it in an online interview as the best
live PA he's ever seen.  We are therefore supremely excited to
welcome this talented young producer and label owner back for
another sweat-soaked dancefloor pummeling before he heads to
Detroit for a headlining set at this year's DEMF.


and from Stockholm, Sweden:

AGARIC aka Patrik Skoog  ** 2 hour live PA **

We Are . Leibe*Detail . Drumcode . Syndikaat

Patrik Skoog began producing in the 90's, originally focusing on
a harder techno sound which brought him global notoriety.
These days he goes by Agaric, an alias with which he delves into
the slower, deeper realms of techno and house.  With over a
decade of production experience and more than 100 vinyl
releases to his name, his extended live performance is sure to
excite chin-strokers and rug-cutters alike.


plus special guest:

MYLES EGNER   ( s.w.a.t . platform . tweekin' )

with resident DJs:

NIKOLA BAYTALA   ( robsoul . junior boys own . s.w.a.t. )
SAMMY D   ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA   ( platform . esdjco )

ALEX UNDER  (aka Friendly People, Musica Charlista)

The deepest meaning of 'collage', defined by Max Ernst, is the general
application of Arthur Rimabaud's 'delirium': "I accustomed myself to simple
hallucination; I saw quite deliberately a mosque instead of a factory, a
drummer's school conducted by angels, carriages on the highways of the sky,
a salon at the bottom of a lake: monsters, mysteries, a vaudeville poster
raising horrors before my eyes."  We could describe collage as an alchemic
compound of two or more heterogeneous elements, derivate by their unexpecte=
d
approximation generated deliberately by the search of systematic confusion
and distorted perception.

That's Alex Under's musical universe. Based in Madrid, this producer is the
'CMYK' label manager. He is also one of the men behind 'Apnea' and
'Bemysheep', and one of the founders of Net28 (the network behind these
labels and others like 'CyclicalTracks' and 'Pulpa'). Alex Under confirmed
himself as the new reality of the best international techno, sometimes bein=
g
minimal and deep, sometimes hard and aggressive, but always original. He
creates a sonic collage combining techno, trance and house elements while h=
e
constructs complex rhythms that arise from the dancefloor, taking the
listeners to a higher level where emotions, depth, mind & body blend in a
unique equation. Alex Under will intrigue beyond your perception.


=3D=3D> LINKS:

Alex Under's website:
http://www.cmykmusik.com/

Alex Under's discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Alex%20Under

CMYK on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/cmykmusik

http://mp3.juno.co.uk/MP3/SF245690-01-02-02.mp3

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Du0F2v-xU7M4


____________________________________________________


AGARIC  (aka Patrik Skoog, Headroom)

After working together with Niklas Ehrlin and Henrik Larsson on their main
and well known project in the 90's, Headroom, Patrik Skoog began a solo
project, darker and more tribal-techno influenced in comparison to the
collaborations.  After releasing the first output on German and American
labels, he then decided to set up Native Diffusion records for these type o=
f
tracks.  This focused mainly on Patrik's own productions, but also showcase=
d
remixes from the likes of Damon Wild, W.J. Henze, Inigo Kennedy, Slobodan,
Takaaki Itoh & Hardcell. As of 2003 and 2004 other talent started to appear
on the label as well, respected producers and newcomers to the techno scene
alike.  2004 also saw Headroom=B4s debut release on the classic New York-la=
bel
Synewave getting licensed to the "Exhibitionist" CD and DVD compilation,
compiled and mixed by world renowned DJ Jeff Mills, and as the popularity o=
f
their style of techno increased over the last years, remix offers also
dropped in frequently. Patrik did one for fellow Swede Adam Beyer on his no=
w
classic Drumcode imprint, which shortly thereafter lead to more releases on
Drumcode, and its sublabel Truesoul.

Being a technical DJ with great sense for momentum and track selection,
Skoog has played and continues to play praised gigs in the US, UK, North-
and South America and all across Europe. In early 2005 a new project was
found in "Agaric" where he explores the slower, deeper realms of techno and
house and with productions on his well-received label project named "We
Are". As Agaric, Patrik has gained appreciation from high-ranking peers, an=
d
fans have seen a big change in performances as well as track work, where he
evolves further and further away from playing the typical "hard" sound for
which he was known, and more often than not performs a deeper variety of
tracks that hints at a modern take on early influences like Robert Hood,
Wolfgang Voigt. and Plastikman, still with high intensity and groove. In
2006, the Native Diffusion label was put on ice, ending after six years at
number 19 in the series, and Patrik started to perform live acts all over
the world with the Agaric project--premiering at one of the leading
festivals for innovative electronic music in the Nordic countries, Public
Service.

In 2007, nearly a decade after his debut on the Loop label and over one
hundred vinyl releases later, Agaric relocated to and got involved in the
ever-evolving electronic music scene in Berlin, Germany, where he now
resides.  His highly-anticipated appearance at [KONTROL] will be one of onl=
y
a handfull of North American performances, including stops in NYC, LA,
Chicago and Detroit.


=3D=3D> LINKS:

Agaric on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/djagaric

Agaric's Discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Agaric%20(2)

We Are Records Website:
http://www.wearerecords.se/

=3D=3D> VIDEO:

Agaric - Live PA in Austin, Texas - 2006

____________________________________________________


MYLES EGNER

Myles Egner grew up in a small town in Iowa and was turned on to the "futur=
e
house sound of Chicago" at a young age.  By age 14 he started mixing with
his brother DJ Rin, playing deep house and ghetto house while attending
warehouse parties in Chicago on the weekends and being influenced by people
like Gene Farris, Paul Johnson, DJ Traxx, and  DJ Funk.

After moving to SF in '94, Myles linked up with S.W.A.T. (Nikola Baytala,
Kwai le Chief, and DJ Rasoul), sat in on studio sessions whenever there was
an empty seat, and soon found himself a resident at their long-running
Friday night weekly at SF's legendary house club The Top.  Over the years
Myles has moved away from and returned to SF several times, working in four
different record stores along the way: Housewares (SF), Aaron's Records and
Beat Non Stop (LA), and most recently Tweekin' Records (SF). His many hours
logged in these shops gave him the opportunity to soak in boundless
influences and of course pick up an arsenal of heaters, from house to
minimal to hard techno.  His uncontested skills behind the decks have lande=
d
him gigs alongside talent including Kenny Larkin, Octave One, Boo Williams,
K. Alexi, Christian Bloch, JPLS, and more.

Myles is currently making a mark on the Bay Area techno scene as a resident
at Platform, Bureau, and Wish, where he can always be counted on to bring a
unique style of "beating the box".  Be it house, minimal, or banging techno=
,
this talented young man is surely one to look out for.


=3D=3D> LINKS:

Myles Egner on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/mylesegner1

Myles Egner - Gilbert Street (160kbs mp3 - 65mins)
http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/Myles%20Egner%20-%20Gilbert%20Street%20-%20160=
.mp3

Radio Integrated is live and on the air NOW! At the moment we're playing a
few electro tunes, to be followed at 10pm by Disconnect's "Head Cleaner"
mix.  So get in your most comfy chair, have a pot cookie, and space out to
some deep, hard, tripped out techno.  Check it out at http://radio
.defsf.com:1200/

* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *
* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *

Tonight on Radio Integrated /// Friday, May 2nd 2008 /// http://radio
.defsf.com:1200/

A classic hard techno mix - DJ Disconnect's "Head Cleaner"

Recorded live on three turntables in 1999/2000, "Head Cleaner" is a great
example of deep, heady, late-90s European techno.  Unless Disconnect gave
you a copy of this tape at a rave in 2001, this is pretty much the only
place you'll hear this mix.  It's on a casette tape even!

Check out the tracklisting and liner notes here:
http://www.defsf.com/people/disconnect

Plus... some modern techno tunes selected by Miss Chelsea Faith


Tune in from 9pm-1am Pacific Time at http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

Subject: [sfraves] so why is 1015 pretending to be another club?

giving the address as 103 Harriet, which is the alley door for 1015, and

easy for people to find the place when they know the name and location
would make sense, or are they trying to feel like it's an underground
address down a little side street?  Or does it just mean 1015 wants to
separate the techno people from the hip hop people?  Have they done this
before?

At 07:08 PM 5/3/2008, Ray Wong wrote:


>Anyone else notice on the Richie Hawtin/M_nus promo stuff that they're
>giving the address as 103 Harriet, which is the alley door for 1015, and
>not mentioning 1015 at all?  Seems odd to me, you'd think making it
>easy for people to find the place when they know the name and location
>would make sense, or are they trying to feel like it's an underground
>address down a little side street?  Or does it just mean 1015 wants to
>separate the techno people from the hip hop people?  Have they done this
>before?


This kind of stuff has gone on for years - different address, 
different directions,
different map point - didn't matter - it always ends up being the 
same old place

Sometimes they do it because the old address had a bad rap - mostly
they do it to seem fresh and new - you should've been around here in the
mid-90s when every party that seemed good or had a decent lineup always
ended up being at 16th and Harrison - "Love American Style", indeed -
still, there were some crazy nites, there - anyone else remember
the "flashlight" party ? - where they handed everyone a cheapo flashlight
as you came in and then realized that flashlights were gonna be the only
light source for the evening

16th and Harrison - there were so many rumors about that place - a lot
of great parties, too. . . . . at least it didn't seem to be the 
firetrap that Acme was.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] so why is 1015 pretending to be another club?



Yes, sort of the point... It happens for many reasons, seems like an odd
time for 1015 these days.  First they said they were getting away from
electronic dance, yet so far none of that's actually changed... now they're
billing a huge show under an alternate address.  1015's one of the longer
running clubs, though nowhere near Endup's 35 years, at around half that
they've had a good run thus far, and I don't think they were something
clublike before they were 1015. 

Perhaps it's damage control on the damage control.  I suspect the whole
"getting away from electronic" statement was trying to get some heat off
for the club shootings earlier in the year, but they angered a lot of
their fans with that... by getting folks out there for a big show, maybe
they figure they'll win some back.

Well, not like they've invited me to host a party there so guess I won't
worry about it. :)

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Genesis 6-9

--0-1386578281-1209889177=:58712
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noah%27s_ark
Noah's Ark was, according to Abrahamic religions, a large vessel built at God's command to save Noah, his family, and a core stock of the world's animals from the Great Flood. The story is told in chapters 6-9 of the book of Genesis, with later variations in the Qur'an and a number of other sources.
Genesis 6-9 tells how God decided to destroy the world because of the wickedness of mankind, selecting Noah, a man "righteous in his generation", instructing him to build an ark and take on board his family and representatives of all the animals and birds. God's flood then destroys all life on earth, but at the height of the deluge "God remembered Noah", and the waters abate and the dry land reappears. The story ends with God entering into a covenant with Noah and his descendants.

f Genesis, with later variations in the Qur'an and a number of other source=
s.

kedness of mankind, selecting Noah, a man "righteous in his generation", in=

ves of all the animals and birds. God's flood then destroys all life on ear=

venant with Noah and his descendants.

On 5 May 2008, pinkko wrote:

> Excellent question.
>
> My take on it would be anyone that voted for Bush contributed directly to
> the war.

Indeed.  But, like Obama, we have the ability to learn from our 
mistakes (see 
http://digg.com/2008_us_elections/Obama_Makes_Sense_on_Meet_the_Press 
for example, where he points out the lessons learned in Ill. wrt a gas 
tax suspension; the oil companies were who profited.).  As such, it's 
possible that not all who voted for him supported the invasion.  As it's 
also possible that not all who voted against him opposed the invasion.

It's incredibly simple and it breaks down like this...

To figure out the average that each of us now owes, divide $500 billion 
dollars by 150 million taxpayers and it comes out to $3,333 dollars per 
person or $666 per year/$55 a month; on the installment, pay as you go, 
plan, for the past 5+ years we've been doing this.

Naturally, some have to pay more than others, (through the nose if 
you're rich, even with the Busch tax cuts, you have noooo idea of the 
pain this causez),  and if you're poor, and can't afford the $2 bucks a 
day in taxes it costs to keep this non-stop occupational party rolling, 
you may just get off with just having to settle your part of the debt 
with nothing more than your arm, leg, eyes, hearing, eyesight, and only 
in very rare, and very, very, extreme cases, your life.

It's really a small sacrifice, Nicht Wahr?

On any given day the remote chance of that happening to you in Iraq are 
2 in 300,000, which is mad slim, find me another war where the number 
has ever been that low.


Now then, all these back of the envelope calculations don't take into 
account the $1.5 trillion smackeroos that we borrowed from the Chinese 
to get the advance we needed to cover the initial costs of our Iraqi 
adventure, so, using the above mafs, the actual debt every American is 
carrying when they pop their eyes open in the morning is closer to $15K 
per person, or, if it were to be payed off in the course of a year, a 
small nut of $40 bucks, or so a day, everyday, including Sunday, 7 days 
a weeks, 52 weeks a year.

That's just the debt.

That doesn't include personal expenses like gas, groceries, utilities, 
rent/mortgage, tuition, insurance, xb/ps/wiis,  doctor's bills, etc etc.

Not that this is any nevermind, since we're Americans and there ain't 
never been a challenge that we that we that we, (wait, wait... /'*how* 
much?!?!' 'wow, you're fucking kidding me')/, oh, fuck wait never mind.

Subject: [sfraves] tuesday techno mix

"Forgot to say about sleeparchive. I have never seen or heard anything  
as boring in my whole life. Bitterly disappointed, I thought it was a  
wind up. I was watching in the chalet and just had to go down to see  
it if it was for real.
A guy standing behind a laptop, almost motionless apart from drinking  
water, playing the most boring minimal, repetitive noises ever. Bleugh."

on the experimental tip, Sleeparchive Live PA at the Electrolounge,  
Freiburg Germany  Feb 2006

http://www.elektro-lounge.de/sound/obj_soundbox/sleeparchive_live@elektrolounge_03-02-2006.mp3

Video of Sleeparchive live at BLOC weekend.
http://www.bloctv.com/bloctv/player/index.html?startPointer=video&startID=62

Sleep Archive is Berliner Stefan Metzger, formerly of Dsseldorf. He  
lives and works in Kreuzberg.

To make matters more confusing, Sleep Archive may or may not be all  
Metzger. If 'Infrared Glow,' the most recent EP, sounds different from  
the first three, well, there's a reason for it: it's someone else.  
Who, exactly, Metzger's not saying. 'Another shy guy from Berlin,' he  
says, laughing over his apple pie.

There's no doubt that Sleep Archive is going for a particular kind of  
throwback identity: the sound of the records, obviously, goes back to  
Vainio's arctic techno and Plastikman's sparsest moments. But the  
rhetoric behind the label as well ? not a total anonymity, but a  
veneer of it, plus the hand-stamped sleeves ? evokes a moment where  
faceless techno bollox was something to be prized, strived for.  
(Working in the shadow of Hardwax, run by the mysterious Basic Channel  
crew, obviously makes this image easier to keep up.) And in an  
industry full of self-promoters, Metzger is refreshingly cynical  
without being bitter. He believes that remixes have more to do with  
marketing than aesthetics (while he's done several now, for Regis and  
Monolake, among others, he won't offer up his own tracks for remixes);  
and he claims that Sleep Archive will never release outside the Sleep  
Archive label. (He hedges a bit when conversation moves to Jeff Mills:  
he would, he admits, release on Axis, if asked.) Even if the  
ultra-autonomous, DIY, slightly suspicious-of-the-world stance feels,  
at times, like a contrivance, I'm glad he's pursuing this path.  
Techno's too glammed up as it is; it needs a little more anonymity, a  
little more mystery. Metzger hints at a coding behind the coloring of  
the Sleep Archive vinyls. When the palette expands beyond the current  
clear, black, and blue, we'll know that more mysteries are in store.

http://www.discogs.com/artist/sleeparchive

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

> Date: Tue, 6 May 2008 14:29:34 -0400
> From: james.hurlbut@utoronto.ca
> To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
> Subject: [sfraves] tuesday techno mix
>=20
> "Forgot to say about sleeparchive. I have never seen or heard anything =20
> as boring in my whole life. Bitterly disappointed, I thought it was a =20
> wind up. I was watching in the chalet and just had to go down to see =20
> it if it was for real.
> A guy standing behind a laptop, almost motionless apart from drinking =20
> water, playing the most boring minimal, repetitive noises ever. Bleugh."
>=20
> on the experimental tip, Sleeparchive Live PA at the Electrolounge, =20
> Freiburg Germany  Feb 2006
>=20
> http://www.elektro-lounge.de/sound/obj_soundbox/sleeparchive_live@elektro=
lounge_03-02-2006.mp3
>=20
> Video of Sleeparchive live at BLOC weekend.
> http://www.bloctv.com/bloctv/player/index.html?startPointer=3Dvideo&start=
ID=3D62
>=20
> Sleep Archive is Berliner Stefan Metzger, formerly of D=FCsseldorf. He =20
> lives and works in Kreuzberg.
>=20
> To make matters more confusing, Sleep Archive may or may not be all =20
> Metzger. If 'Infrared Glow,' the most recent EP, sounds different from =20
> the first three, well, there's a reason for it: it's someone else. =20
> Who, exactly, Metzger's not saying. 'Another shy guy from Berlin,' he =20
> says, laughing over his apple pie.
>=20
> There's no doubt that Sleep Archive is going for a particular kind of =20
> throwback identity: the sound of the records, obviously, goes back to =20
> Vainio's arctic techno and Plastikman's sparsest moments. But the =20
> rhetoric behind the label as well ? not a total anonymity, but a =20
> veneer of it, plus the hand-stamped sleeves ? evokes a moment where =20
> faceless techno bollox was something to be prized, strived for. =20
> (Working in the shadow of Hardwax, run by the mysterious Basic Channel =20
> crew, obviously makes this image easier to keep up.) And in an =20
> industry full of self-promoters, Metzger is refreshingly cynical =20
> without being bitter. He believes that remixes have more to do with =20
> marketing than aesthetics (while he's done several now, for Regis and =20
> Monolake, among others, he won't offer up his own tracks for remixes); =20
> and he claims that Sleep Archive will never release outside the Sleep =20
> Archive label. (He hedges a bit when conversation moves to Jeff Mills: =20
> he would, he admits, release on Axis, if asked.) Even if the =20
> ultra-autonomous, DIY, slightly suspicious-of-the-world stance feels, =20
> at times, like a contrivance, I'm glad he's pursuing this path. =20
> Techno's too glammed up as it is; it needs a little more anonymity, a =20
> little more mystery. Metzger hints at a coding behind the coloring of =20
> the Sleep Archive vinyls. When the palette expands beyond the current =20
> clear, black, and blue, we'll know that more mysteries are in store.
>=20
> http://www.discogs.com/artist/sleeparchive
>=20

Make Magazine + Making Things + Cycling74/Max/MSP =

You use 
http://cycling74.com/products/makekit

To control/be controlled by:
http://www.makingthings.com/
http://www.makingthings.com/products
http://www.makingthings.com/documentation/how-to

And they even include hacks for making your own breadboards, connecting to 
higher current servos, wireless, if that's not enough.

Mad Professor Hairdo Not Included...

I love it, a ready to go physical interface that speaks OSC and USB, 
interfaces with a host of common sensors and actuators, with standard open 
protocols to several programming languages (ruby, python, flash, 
processing, c#...).

And it's not all that spendy.

Seriously, the only thing that I can see that sucks about it is the 3.3v 
standard for in/out CV controls.  Would be nice if it had 5 and 12v 
options as well.  But nothing that can't be worked around.  :)

andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy

05/14/08 Edition:
=20
Special Guest DJ:
Evinrude (NetAmp/Stimulus - SF)

One of the last remaining vinyl-exclusive DJs in the Bay, Evinrude has been=
 addicted to electronic music, and hunting down and spinning 12-inch gems, =
for ten years. A drummer for thirteen years (and a pianist for eight) prior=
 to selling his soul to the gods of beats, it was, as they say, all over on=
ce he was properly introduced to electronic music: he sold his drums shortl=
y thereafter to buy turntables and a mixer.
=20
=20
E'rude started doing his thing in the San Francisco rave scene back around =
2000 as acid/hard trance/energy/breaks slinger Darth (Darth Evan before tha=
t, a given name that he never really enjoyed). After a several-year hiatus,=
 he dove back in and started the breaks weekly Broke-Ass with cohorts Dirt =
and Nugz, and the monthly Smoke Breaks, both at @lpha bar in SF =96 and for=
 a short time before the long closing of the club for remodeling, he also d=
id Crooked at Nickie's in SF. In the spring of 2006, Evan joined San Franci=
sco's/Black Rock City's Space Cowboys, and now enjoys helping run the show =
at NetAmp Radio =96 the Wednesday night SF-based show on nuskoolbreaks. co.=
 uk =96 and Stimulus, a semi-regular event that helped to pave the way for =
the Electrotech sound's explosion in the Bay Area.
=20

 w/ Residents:
Justin Johnson (Cable Recordings / Barely Legal Records / Kingsize-USA - SF=
/NYC)
Marc(O) (OtherWorld / Cable Wednesdays / The MidnightSons - SF/DC )

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: The Ozone Hole is for sale on eBay?

I know *I've* seen a lot of strange things up for bid on eBay over the years, 
many of them getting taken down by eBay itself.  But here's one that's both 
strange and results on plenty of good happening.  You can buy the ozone hole on 
eBay: http://www.joketribe.com/products/The.Ozone.Hole.On.Ebay.php

Now, what you get if you buy the ozone hole is that you end up sponsoring 
theozonehole.com for one year.  That website utilizes scientific data from 
government agencies across the globe (yes, not just the easily influenced U.S. 
ones) to track the state of the gaping wound in our atmosphere which is the 
ozone hole.  (And apparently over 2.3 million people visited the site last 
year; a statistic than generally only grows over time.  At that level of 
traffic your purchase is definitely a reasonable rate in the internet world.)

I'm sure there's got to be SOME environmental website out there who could use 
the exposure.


--

AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)

"Opinions are my own only, and do not necessarily represent those of
KZSU Radio or Stanford University." (or words to that effect.)

minimal techno like Mike Ink or Studio 1 than most other new stuff.

audience.

On Tue, 6 May 2008 dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
-&e->I always measure the quality of techno by how much code I write when 
-&e->listening to it.  That's how I started listening to techno and house 
-&e->back in the early nineties and still how I listen much of the time at 
-&e->work.
-&e->
-&e->I don't find minimal to be very productive code wise in general, but 
-&e->this mix really put me to sleep.  Aptly named.
-&e->
-&e->Sonorous.  Boring.  Lacking in funk.
-&e->
-&e->:(
-&e->
-&e->Peter

Don't get me wrong here... I like minimal (and have a ton of classic 
minimal techno in my collection), but as a color or a mood.  I don't 
really understand whole sets of the stuff... it's like watching only 
movies that are apocalyptic science fiction, or pirate flicks without 
parrots.  What I love most about techno is that it's all that minimal 
stuff we're talking about, but it's also face ripping hard shit, kooky DJ 
Rush style jackin stuff, weird electro influenced stuff, borderline IDM, 
tech house, tech funk, tribal, etc and it's got a long rich history... you 
can put stuff from last year with stuff from '92 right on top of each 
other.  You can make it with any gear, ever... from a 909 and a 303 to 
loop tools to virtual analog software to a modular to geeky algorhythm 
stuff.  It's the "biggest" of the EDM genres except maybe house, and 
allows you so much room to move, I don't understand why people close 
themselves off to some hyphenated corner of that world when they can have 
it all.

The fun to me, both as a DJ and on the other side of the decks is in 
traversing colors, and trying to make a bigger ride out of those elements, 
and doing it a different way every time.  Heres one of my more genre 
hopping sets (but still including lots of minimal tunes here and there 
throughout).

>From the August 10th, 2004 Epiphany of Sound show:

----- Original Message ----
From: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>
To: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
Cc: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Wednesday, May 7, 2008 1:40:27 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] tuesday techno mix


On Tue, 6 May 2008 dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
-&e->I always measure the quality of techno by how much code I write when 
-&e->listening to it.  That's how I started listening to techno and house 
-&e->back in the early nineties and still how I listen much of the time at 
-&e->work.
-&e->
-&e->I don't find minimal to be very productive code wise in general, but 
-&e->this mix really put me to sleep.  Aptly named.
-&e->
-&e->Sonorous.  Boring.  Lacking in funk.
-&e->
-&e->:(
-&e->
-&e->Peter

Don't get me wrong here... I like minimal (and have a ton of classic 
minimal techno in my collection), but as a color or a mood.  I don't 
really understand whole sets of the stuff... it's like watching only 
movies that are apocalyptic science fiction, or pirate flicks without 
parrots.  What I love most about techno is that it's all that minimal 
stuff we're talking about, but it's also face ripping hard shit, kooky DJ 
Rush style jackin stuff, weird electro influenced stuff, borderline IDM, 
tech house, tech funk, tribal, etc and it's got a long rich history... you 
can put stuff from last year with stuff from '92 right on top of each 
other.  You can make it with any gear, ever... from a 909 and a 303 to 
loop tools to virtual analog software to a modular to geeky algorhythm 
stuff.  It's the "biggest" of the EDM genres except maybe house, and 
allows you so much room to move, I don't understand why people close 
themselves off to some hyphenated corner of that world when they can have 
it all.

The fun to me, both as a DJ and on the other side of the decks is in 
traversing colors, and trying to make a bigger ride out of those elements, 
and doing it a different way every time.  Heres one of my more genre 
hopping sets (but still including lots of minimal tunes here and there 
throughout).

>From the August 10th, 2004 Epiphany of Sound show:
http://www.saturn5.com/andy/andyw-eos.mp3

Thanks JC + KZSU for recording it!
andy'your resident grumpy has-been techno guy'w

Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR: The Ozone Hole is for sale on eBay?

it's real, and it's older than me:

<i>The discovery of the Antarctic "ozone hole" by British Antarctic 
Survey scientists Farman, Gardiner and Shanklin (announced in a paper 
in Nature in May 1985) came as a shock to the scientific community, 
because the observed decline in polar ozone was far larger than 
anyone had anticipated.[citation needed] Satellite measurements 
showing massive depletion of ozone around the south pole were 
becoming available at the same time. However, these were initially 
rejected as unreasonable by data quality control algorithms (they 
were filtered out as errors since the values were unexpectedly low); 
the ozone hole was detected only in satellite data when the raw data 
was reprocessed following evidence of ozone depletion in in situ 
observations. When the software was rerun without the flags, the 
ozone hole was seen as far back as 1976. [40]</i>

from:

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ozone_hole#The_Ozone_Hole


sarilion

At 07:55 PM 5/6/2008, you wrote:


>There's still a myth about a "hole" in the ozone layer?

>ever done so...it's more of a giant cloud type thing. Not to say 
>it's not being depleted, but it doesn't have any "holes" in it, it's 
>just dwindling, hehe.

> > theozonehole.com for one year.  That website utilizes scientific data from
> > government agencies across the globe (yes, not just the easily 
> influenced U.S.
> > ones) to track the state of the gaping wound in our atmosphere 
> which is the
> > ozone hole.  (And apparently over 2.3 million people visited the site last
> > year; a statistic than generally only grows over time.  At that level of

This FRIDAY, May 9th.... It's Radio Integrated: Banana Daquiri* edition with
DJs Snoek and Raf One

Snoek a.k.a That Fucking Guy. . .  (www.myspace.com/snoek)

Snoek (aka That Fucking Guy/Meekrob) has been digging techno in most of its
forms since the mid 90s. He is excited to be part of the Bay Area techno
scene and to contribute his own style, homegrown in Holland and the Middle
East. As a producer and DJ, his only mantra is that it has to be extra nice
for everybody. Snoek has been involved with the Soma Tech parties and is
currently involved in SICK!.. a bi-monthly party on Sixth & Mission in SF.

and...

RafOne . . . (www.myspace.com/goldcode)

Raf is a guy we've been seeing around for years but somehow have never
booked.... but on Friday that changes! He's always brought a little
something different to the mix; a blend of techno, electro, disco, house,
italo, acid, and everything in between.  Check his music blog at
www.gold-code.net for a sampling of his eclectic and refined taste.


Tune in at :

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

Every Friday from 9pm - 1am Pacific Time

Contact : radiointegrated@gmail.com  www.myspace.com/radiointegrated

For updates on DEF and San Francisco Bay Area techno
news and info, sign up for the DEF list at
def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com

For Radio Integrated updates:
radio-integrated-subscribe@defsf.com


///Radio Integrated :: radiointegrated@gmail.com ::
http://radio.defsf.com:1200/  ::
Broadcasting live from Bliss Factory Studios, Alameda, CA///


*BYOB - Bring Your Own Blender

=20
****note - the last few Cable nights have been slammin'! Come on down and j=
oin the fun!!! As always it's FREE!!! (plus, those 2 for 1 Smirnoff Vodka d=
rinks really hit the spot if you are broke!!!)

> Cable Recordings and Shine present:

> *~*CABLE WEDNESDAYS*~*

> Every 2nd and 4th Wednesday @ SHINE
> 9pm - 2am
> 21+

> funkysleazydirtygroovybanginspacediscohouseandbreaks
=20
> 05/14/08 Edition:

Special Guest DJ's:
DJ Mes (www.guesthouserecords.com)

Mes began his journey through the dance music industry when he was
first exposed to house in 1993. While growing up in the San Francisco
Bay area, his musical passion was fueled by soul, funk, and disco of
the seventies, as well as eighties electro, hip-hop, and jazz. Drawing
on the influences of friends Tony (Tango Records) and DJ Dan (Funky
Techno Tribe) and Rob Drake (THC), Mes found a way to meld all of his
early musical influences into a deep, yet driving and funky sound that
allowed him to gain quick recognition in the house music scene. Early
recognition of his talent and unique sound gave him the opportunity to
play at the legendary Area 51 parties, as well as other now infamous
events like The Gathering, Freedom, and The Burning Man Festival.


In 1996, he took his involvement in the music industry to the next
level when he co-founded Daddy's Records with partners, Rob Doten
(Wicked, Greyhound Records) and Buna (Wicked, E.T.I., Oboro Records).
Based in Berkley, California, Daddy's Records became an influential
label and record store. After DJing, overseeing label releases, the
next logical step was to produce his own music. After the release of
his first single on Kick Drum his focus, and passion for production
coupled with his DJ career, continued to grow steadily. It is the
passion for creating the music he fell in love with that has allowed
him to have multiple releases out on labels like: BlackCherry, AJ, Safe
in Sound, DAE, Big Popsicle, MVM, Public Access, Sunny Day, and
GoodFamily.
Mes's production talents have not only earned him local and
international respect, his skills as a DJ have made him a highly sought
after commodity. He began his first out of state residency at Spin
Cycle in Reno, Nevada where he continued to pack the floor for the next
four years. His residency at Spin Cycle was just the beginning of what
has now become a whirl-wind of gigs that have taken him far and near,
spanning cities and countries such as: Chicago, Dallas, Austin, Miami,
Orlando, Cincinnati, Indianapolis,  San Diego, L.A., Brazil, Belgium,
France, Spain, Scotland, Netherlands and the U.K. Currently, Mes lends
his DJ skills to clubs and parties in the Bay area like: Stylus, Aural
Confection, Simma' Down Now, Shake Your Booty and Underground's, while
continuing to bring his deep and driving rhythms to venues around the
world.
Along with Mes's well known skills as a dj and producer, he also
handles the day to day responsibilities for his own record label
"Guesthouse Music". One of the top labels in the burgeoning new school
of underground - part of the forward-thinking house music movement in
the United States. Started by Mes in early 2005, the label already has
seven releases under its nine-month old belt, and is showing no signs
of losing momentum. Inspired by the close-knit vibe of the underground
house community in the US and beyond, (and from plenty of couch-surfing
and sleeping at friends' places while DJing away from home) the name
Guesthouse was born; and so was the home of what Sutton hopes will be
the future classics of house music. Whether Mes is producing or DJing
it is his never ending energy and drive to put his signature on the
dance music community that makes him a talent not to be missed. =20
> Evinrude (NetAmp/Stimulus - SF)

> One of the last remaining vinyl-exclusive DJs in the Bay, Evinrude has be=
en addicted to electronic music, and hunting down and spinning 12-inch gems=
, for ten years. A drummer for thirteen years (and a pianist for eight) pri=
or to selling his soul to the gods of beats, it was, as they say, all over =
once he was properly introduced to electronic music: he sold his drums shor=
tly thereafter to buy turntables and a mixer.
=20
> E'rude started doing his thing in the San Francisco rave scene back aroun=
d 2000 as acid/hard trance/energy/breaks slinger Darth (Darth Evan before t=
hat, a given name that he never really enjoyed). After a several-year hiatu=
s, he dove back in and started the breaks weekly Broke-Ass with cohorts Dir=
t and Nugz, and the monthly Smoke Breaks, both at @lpha bar in SF =96 and f=
or a short time before the long closing of the club for remodeling, he also=
 did Crooked at Nickie's in SF. In the spring of 2006, Evan joined San Fran=
cisco's/Black Rock City's Space Cowboys, and now enjoys helping run the sho=
w at NetAmp Radio =96 the Wednesday night SF-based show on nuskoolbreaks. c=
o. uk =96 and Stimulus, a semi-regular event that helped to pave the way fo=
r the Electrotech sound's explosion in the Bay Area.

Subject: [sfraves] From the DEF vaults... Paradigm Shift, 2003

------=_Part_29656_18888091.1210279284045
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

I was cleaning my house the other day and happened to come across a CD with
all the audio from DEF's first party, Paradigm Shift.  Score!  I knew the
party had been recorded, but I figured the files were long lost. I put
together a little Paradigm Shift page on defsf.com with audio and photos, so
if you'd care to take a trip down memory lane (and get pummeled by some
fast, hard techno), check it out here:

www.defsf.com/archives/paradigmshift


Love Chelsea


P.S. - I remember there being some really kick-ass blacklight photos from
this party, which I saw at one point but never got copies of.  Are those
still floating around? Anyone know their whereabouts?  My photos from this
party aren't that great... I think they were taken on a disposable camera.

------=_Part_29656_18888091.1210279284045--

Alain Octavo (Spundae/ alainoctavo. com)

An integral part of San Francisco's dance culture, Alain began his
profession in 1995 producing underground events at legendary venues around
the San Francisco Bay Area. By the following year, his innovative ideas
created a growing kinship with industry professionals throughout
California co-producing events the west coast has never experienced and
shattering every attendance record to date.


Speeding ahead with this momentum, his musical versatility has landed him
more featured nights than any other DJ at the world renowned Ruby Skye,
one of North America's nominated best nightclubs. Just in recent years he
has shared the bill and exclusively opened for producers: Armin Van
Buuren, Ferry Corsten, Jeff Mills, Carl Cox, Basement Jaxx, John Digweed,
Satoshi Tomiie, Benny Benassi, Roger Sanchez, BT, Steve Lawler, Markus
Schulz, Hernan Cattaneo and much more. In 2007 he was the only DJ in San
Francisco invited to play annual anniversaries such as: Spundae, Ruby
Skye, Skills, Opel and Qool along with one of the most memorable moments
being a sunset performance in front of 65,000 people on the largest float
at the San Francisco LoveFest.



Along with residents:

Aaron Jae
Bam
M.O.D.

Tonight! May 9th, 2008 . . . It's Radio Integrated: Banana Daquiri* edition
with DJs Snoek and Raf Onehttp://radio.defsf.com:1200/ : : : 9pm-1am Pacific
: : : Broadcasting live from Bliss Factory Studios

Snoek a.k.a That Fucking Guy. . .  (www.myspace.com/snoek)

Snoek (aka That Fucking Guy/Meekrob) has been digging techno in most of its
forms since the mid 90s. He is excited to be part of the Bay Area techno
scene and to contribute his own style, homegrown in Holland and the Middle
East. As a producer and DJ, his only mantra is that it has to be extra nice
for everybody. Snoek has been involved with the Soma Tech parties and is
currently involved in SICK!.. a bi-monthly party on Sixth & Mission in SF.

and...

RafOne . . . (www.myspace.com/goldcode)

Raf is a guy we've been seeing around for years but somehow have never
booked.... but on Friday that changes! He's always brought a little
something different to the mix; a blend of techno, electro, disco, house,
italo, acid, and everything in between.  Check his music blog at
www.gold-code.net for a sampling of his eclectic and refined taste.


Tune in at :

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

Every Friday from 9pm - 1am Pacific Time

Contact : radiointegrated@gmail.com  www.myspace.com/radiointegrated

For updates on DEF and San Francisco Bay Area techno
news and info, sign up for the DEF list at
def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com

For Radio Integrated updates:
radio-integrated-subscribe@defsf.com

Radio Integrated is on the air NOW! Tune in for some lovely techno tunes as
selected by Chelsea Faith. Coming up at 9pm we'll have sets from Raf One and
Snoek, so listen up!

Tonight! May 9th, 2008 . . . It's Radio Integrated: Banana Daquiri* edition
with DJs Snoek and Raf Onehttp://radio.defsf.com:1200/ : : : 9pm-1am Pacific
: : : Broadcasting live from Bliss Factory Studios

Snoek a.k.a That Fucking Guy. . .  (www.myspace.com/snoek)

Snoek (aka That Fucking Guy/Meekrob) has been digging techno in most of its
forms since the mid 90s. He is excited to be part of the Bay Area techno
scene and to contribute his own style, homegrown in Holland and the Middle
East. As a producer and DJ, his only mantra is that it has to be extra nice
for everybody. Snoek has been involved with the Soma Tech parties and is
currently involved in SICK!.. a bi-monthly party on Sixth & Mission in SF.

and...

RafOne . . . (www.myspace.com/goldcode)

Raf is a guy we've been seeing around for years but somehow have never
booked.... but on Friday that changes! He's always brought a little
something different to the mix; a blend of techno, electro, disco, house,
italo, acid, and everything in between.  Check his music blog at
www.gold-code.net for a sampling of his eclectic and refined taste.


Tune in at :

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

Every Friday from 9pm - 1am Pacific Time

Contact : radiointegrated@gmail.com  www.myspace.com/radiointegrated

For updates on DEF and San Francisco Bay Area techno
news and info, sign up for the DEF list at
def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com

For Radio Integrated updates:
radio-integrated-subscribe@defsf.com


///Radio Integrated :: radiointegrated@gmail.com ::
http://radio.defsf.com:1200/  ::
Broadcasting live from Bliss Factory Studios, Alameda, CA///


*BYOB - Bring Your Own Blender

Snoek a.k.a That Fucking Guy. . . (www.myspace.com/snoek)

Snoek (aka That Fucking Guy/Meekrob) has been digging techno in most of its
forms since the mid 90s. He is excited to be part of the Bay Area techno
scene and to contribute his own style, homegrown in Holland and the Middle
East. As a producer and DJ, his only mantra is that it has to be extra nice
for everybody. Snoek has been involved with the Soma Tech parties and is
currently involved in SICK!.. a bi-monthly party on Sixth & Mission in SF.

and...

RafOne . . . (www.myspace.com/goldcode)

Raf is a guy we've been seeing around for years but somehow have never
booked.... but on Friday that changes! He's always brought a little
something different to the mix; a blend of techno, electro, disco, house,
italo, acid, and everything in between. Check his music blog at
www.gold-code.net for a sampling of his eclectic and refined taste.


Tune in at :

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

Every Friday from 9pm - 1am Pacific Time

>> Snoek a.k.a That Fucking Guy. . .  (www.myspace.com/snoek)
>>
>> Snoek (aka That Fucking Guy/Meekrob) has been digging techno in most of =
its
>> forms since the mid 90s. He is excited to be part of the Bay Area techno
>> scene and to contribute his own style, homegrown in Holland and the Midd=
le
>> East. As a producer and DJ, his only mantra is that it has to be extra n=
ice
>> for everybody. Snoek has been involved with the Soma Tech parties and is
>> currently involved in SICK!.. a bi-monthly party on Sixth & Mission in S=
F.
>>
>> and...
>>
>> RafOne . . . (www.myspace.com/goldcode)
>>
>> Raf is a guy we've been seeing around for years but somehow have never
>> booked.... but on Friday that changes! He's always brought a little
>> something different to the mix; a blend of techno, electro, disco, house=
,
>> italo, acid, and everything in between.  Check his music blog at
>> www.gold-code.net for a sampling of his eclectic and refined taste.
