Newsom envisions dancing in S.F. streets

Cecilia M. Vega, Chronicle Staff Writer

Saturday, May 10, 2008

Paris turns the banks of the Seine into a palm tree-studded, sandy- 
beach hangout in the summertime, and Bogota, Colombia, bans cars from  
its busy thoroughfares once a week and gives free aerobics classes in  
the streets.

So why can't a think-outside-the-box city like San Francisco  
occasionally close its main drag and offer tai chi sessions along the  
waterfront and let people jog wherever they please?

That's the question Mayor Gavin Newsom is asking as he and his staff  
float a plan to close a 3 1/2-mile stretch of roadway - from the  
Bayview neighborhood on the eastern edge of the city to Chinatown,  
including half the length of the Embarcadero - allowing dance troupes  
to literally dance in the streets, cyclists to ride freely without  
worrying about cars, and yogis to lay down their mats in the shadow of  
the Bay Bridge.

"Instead of bringing people to open space," Newsom said, "we bring  
open space to people."

Mayoral staff members have been working in recent months to turn that  
vision into a reality, bringing on board activists and groups like the  
San Francisco Bicycle Coalition and Walk San Francisco to help sell  
the plan to neighborhoods and city lawmakers.

While the plan might sound idyllic, turning it into reality in San  
Francisco undoubtedly will be difficult.

It is, after all, the same city that took nearly a decade to agree on  
a comprise that barred vehicles from Golden Gate Park on some  
Saturdays and where a proposal to ban private cars from Market Street  
to make it more pedestrian- and bike-friendly sparked such protest  
that it never came to fruition.

A few trial runs

Newsom said he wants to roll out a pilot program from 9 a.m. to 1 p.m.  
on a couple of Sundays in August or September. He's bracing for the  
controversy and said he knows there will be "kinks and concerns of  
neighbors who don't like street closures.

"There is plenty of time to work through that," he said.

The exact road closures have not yet been determined, but the  
preliminary plan stretches from the Bayview Opera House on Third  
Street to the Embarcadero along the waterfront and ends at Portsmouth  
Square in Chinatown. Cross traffic would be allowed at certain points  
along the route.

Officials don't yet know which streets they would close to connect the  
route to Chinatown. They also say objections from residents could  
force them to cut out certain streets - or even neighborhoods -  
altogether.

"If we're a world-class city, then let's act like a world-class city  
and create a sense of city pride and take advantage of our unique  
character," said Newsom, who told staffers about his idea earlier this  
year after returning from the World Economic Forum in Davos,  
Switzerland.

Newsom aides said the mayor hopes that shutting down the Embarcadero  
will encourage people to participate in water activities such as  
kayaking. Newsom said he also believes the road closures would link  
certain communities, like the Bayview, to open-space areas they now  
lack.

Financial District ruled out

Newsom initially had suggested closing the Financial District to cars  
on Sundays so that bikers and pedestrians could roam freely through  
the city's main downtown corridors. But aides looked into the idea and  
determined the tall skyscrapers and narrow streets would make for a  
windy and unappealing destination.

Any temporary street closures would require Newsom's office to obtain  
a permit. It is unclear how the city, which faces a $305 million  
budget deficit, would cover related expenses such as overtime for  
parking-control officers who would likely have to set up roadblocks  
and direct traffic.

"It sounds wonderful," said Gerry Crowley, a neighborhood activist who  
lives on Telegraph Hill, which overlooks the Embarcadero and  
waterfront. "But it seems a little pie-in-the-sky to me."

'Just as pleasant as can be'

The Embarcadero is already packed with residents and tourists walking,  
jogging, in-line skating and pushing strollers nearly all day, every  
day, Crowley said. Banning cars from the bustling street would  
inevitably reroute traffic into nearby neighborhoods, she said.

"You can walk anywhere on the Embarcadero now," she said. "It's just  
as pleasant as can be. We have views of the water and the bridge. What  
about using Ferry Park for the yoga classes?"

Marsha Pendergrass, president of the Bayview Hill Neighborhood  
Association, said she has concerns about what closing any portion of a  
corridor like Third Street could mean for businesses.

"If I was a merchant along that route, I'd be screaming bloody  
murder," she said. "I don't know why you would do this. Are there not  
enough recreation places in San Francisco?"


-- Watch a video of the street closure program in Colombia at  
links.sfgate.com/ZDHY.

"No wonder kids grow up crazy," the midget says. "A cat's cradle is  
nothing but a bunch of X's between somebody's hands, and little kids  
look and look and look at all those X's..."
"And?"
"No damn cat, and no damn cradle."
-Kurt Vonnegut

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] a little Mother's Day history lesson

--Apple-Mail-5-285046508
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset=US-ASCII;
	format=flowed;
	delsp=yes
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

In the United States, Mother's Day was loosely inspired by the British  
day and was imported by social activist Julia Ward Howe after the  
American Civil War. However, it was intended as a call to unite women  
against war. In 1870, she wrote the Mother's Day Proclamation as a  
call for peace and disarmament:

Mother's Day Proclamation

     Arise, then, women of this day!
     Arise, all women who have hearts,
     Whether our baptism be of water or of tears!

     Say firmly:
     "We will not have great questions decided by irrelevant agencies,
     Our husbands will not come to us, reeking with carnage, for  
caresses and applause.
     Our sons shall not be taken from us to unlearn
     All that we have been able to teach them of charity, mercy and  
patience.
     We, the women of one country, will be too tender of those of  
another country
     To allow our sons to be trained to injure theirs."

     From the bosom of the devastated Earth a voice goes up with our  
own.
     It says: "Disarm! Disarm! The sword of murder is not the balance  
of justice."
     Blood does not wipe out dishonor, nor violence indicate possession.
     As men have often forsaken the plough and the anvil at the  
summons of war,
     Let women now leave all that may be left of home for a great and  
earnest day of counsel.

     Let them meet first, as women, to bewail and commemorate the dead.
     Let them solemnly take counsel with each other as to the means
     Whereby the great human family can live in peace,
     Each bearing after his own time the sacred impress, not of Caesar,
     But of God.

     In the name of womanhood and humanity, I earnestly ask
     That a general congress of women without limit of nationality
     May be appointed and held at someplace deemed most convenient
     And at the earliest period consistent with its objects,
     To promote the alliance of the different nationalities,
     The amicable settlement of international questions,
     The great and general interests of peace.
--Apple-Mail-5-285046508--

Swedish_Military_Caught_Firing_Weapons_in_the_Nude

Commander tried to suppress film of naked shooting

Published: 12 May 08 11:56 CET

Lars-Olof Corneliusson, the former commander of a Swedish amphibious =20
military unit based near Stockholm, is accused of trying to cover up =20
an incident in which new conscripts fired shoulder mounted artillery =20
cannons while in the nude.

Gender-neutral military conscription proposed (25 Feb 08)
Sweden makes moves to scrap conscription (6 Dec 07)
Naked soldiers film condemned (31 May 06)
The leader of the exercise, which took place in 2004 and involved =20
soldiers from the Amf 1 amphibious unit based in Vaxholm outside of =20
Stockholm, was told by Corneliusson to destroy a film of the =20
shooting, according to the Dagens Nyheter (DN) newspaper.

When the film was shown by Svergies Television=92s investigative news =20=

program Uppdrag Granskning in May of 2006, it generated a great deal =20
of controversy.

The film shows a group of conscripts from Amf 1 shooting a shoulder-=20
fired mortar wearing only helmets, and generated concern about a lack =20=

of security within the unit.

But of the Corneliusson, who was in charge of the unit at the time, =20
had had his way, the film never would have been made public.

According to DN, Corneliusson had requested that the leader of the =20
exercise destroy the film during a discussion between the two =20
following the incident.

He also failed to report the shooting as a workplace incident, =20
according to the newspaper, which reviewed reports from the unit.

Commander Christer Olofsson, who conducted the military=92s own =20
investigation into the naked artillery firing, was critical of the =20
unit=92s leadership for not reacting immediately following the incident.

Corneliusson is currently under indictment for workplace crimes in =20
connection with a combat patrol boat accident near the island of =20
Sollenkroka in Stockholm=92s archipelago in which two conscripts lost =20=

their lives.

The boating accident took place about one week following the naked =20
shooting incident. A judgment in the case is expected to be handed =20
down on May 27th.

To see the film in question, visit The Local's blog post.

TT/David Landes (news@thelocal.se)

>> Cable Recordings and Shine present:

>> 05/14/08 Edition:
>
> Special Guest DJ's:
> DJ Mes (www.guesthouserecords.com)
>
> Mes began his journey through the dance music industry when he was
> first exposed to house in 1993. While growing up in the San Francisco
> Bay area, his musical passion was fueled by soul, funk, and disco of
> the seventies, as well as eighties electro, hip-hop, and jazz. Drawing
> on the influences of friends Tony (Tango Records) and DJ Dan (Funky
> Techno Tribe) and Rob Drake (THC), Mes found a way to meld all of his
> early musical influences into a deep, yet driving and funky sound that
> allowed him to gain quick recognition in the house music scene. Early
> recognition of his talent and unique sound gave him the opportunity to
> play at the legendary Area 51 parties, as well as other now infamous
> events like The Gathering, Freedom, and The Burning Man Festival.
>
> In 1996, he took his involvement in the music industry to the next
> level when he co-founded Daddy's Records with partners, Rob Doten
> (Wicked, Greyhound Records) and Buna (Wicked, E.T.I., Oboro Records).
> Based in Berkley, California, Daddy's Records became an influential
> label and record store. After DJing, overseeing label releases, the
> next logical step was to produce his own music. After the release of
> his first single on Kick Drum his focus, and passion for production
> coupled with his DJ career, continued to grow steadily. It is the
> passion for creating the music he fell in love with that has allowed
> him to have multiple releases out on labels like: BlackCherry, AJ, Safe
> in Sound, DAE, Big Popsicle, MVM, Public Access, Sunny Day, and
> GoodFamily.

> Mes's production talents have not only earned him local and
> international respect, his skills as a DJ have made him a highly sought
> after commodity. He began his first out of state residency at Spin
> Cycle in Reno, Nevada where he continued to pack the floor for the next
> four years. His residency at Spin Cycle was just the beginning of what
> has now become a whirl-wind of gigs that have taken him far and near,
> spanning cities and countries such as: Chicago, Dallas, Austin, Miami,
> Orlando, Cincinnati, Indianapolis,  San Diego, L.A., Brazil, Belgium,
> France, Spain, Scotland, Netherlands and the U.K. Currently, Mes lends
> his DJ skills to clubs and parties in the Bay area like: Stylus, Aural
> Confection, Simma' Down Now, Shake Your Booty and Underground's, while
> continuing to bring his deep and driving rhythms to venues around the
> world.

> Along with Mes's well known skills as a dj and producer, he also
> handles the day to day responsibilities for his own record label
> "Guesthouse Music". One of the top labels in the burgeoning new school
> of underground - part of the forward-thinking house music movement in
> the United States. Started by Mes in early 2005, the label already has
> seven releases under its nine-month old belt, and is showing no signs
> of losing momentum. Inspired by the close-knit vibe of the underground
> house community in the US and beyond, (and from plenty of couch-surfing
> and sleeping at friends' places while DJing away from home) the name
> Guesthouse was born; and so was the home of what Sutton hopes will be
> the future classics of house music. Whether Mes is producing or DJing
> it is his never ending energy and drive to put his signature on the
> dance music community that makes him a talent not to be missed.

> Evinrude (NetAmp/Stimulus - SF)

> One of the last remaining vinyl-exclusive DJs in the Bay, Evinrude has be=
en addicted to electronic music, and hunting down and spinning 12-inch gems=
, for ten years. A drummer for thirteen years (and a pianist for eight) pri=
or to selling his soul to the gods of beats, it was, as they say, all over =
once he was properly introduced to electronic music: he sold his drums shor=
tly thereafter to buy turntables and a mixer.

>> E'rude started doing his thing in the San Francisco rave scene back arou=
nd 2000 as acid/hard trance/energy/breaks slinger Darth (Darth Evan before =
that, a given name that he never really enjoyed). After a several-year hiat=
us, he dove back in and started the breaks weekly Broke-Ass with cohorts Di=
rt and Nugz, and the monthly Smoke Breaks, both at @lpha bar in SF =96 and =
for a short time before the long closing of the club for remodeling, he als=
o did Crooked at Nickie's in SF. In the spring of 2006, Evan joined San Fra=
ncisco's/Black Rock City's Space Cowboys, and now enjoys helping run the sh=
ow at NetAmp Radio =96 the Wednesday night SF-based show on nuskoolbreaks. =
co. uk =96 and Stimulus, a semi-regular event that helped to pave the way f=
or the Electrotech sound's explosion in the Bay Area.

Marcel Dettmann - Mixmag 006 Podcast
http://www.mixmag.ru/?action=3DPodcastDownload&num=3D6

Marcel Dettmann, who was born in the GDR in 1977 and raised with =20
east-german youth culture. Influenced by EBM and Wave he faces the =20
offspring of virgin Techno in early nineties=E2=80=99s Berlin and gets =20
socialized with this new-born subcultural scene, whose way of life he =20
shall live and develop until today. On the one hand, he has played =20
records since 1994 including residency continuum at Berlin=E2=80=99s =20
Ostgut/Berghain right from its opening in 1999. On the other, Dettmann =20
started to produce and release tracks and remixes in 2006. Beside =20
Ostgut Ton first and foremost his self-run label MDR provides the =20
necessary and appropriate outlet: no compromise, free, independent, =20
facilitating the =E2=80=9Cquest for the optimal track=E2=80=9D. His engageme=
nt at =20
Berlin=E2=80=99s Technosaur Hard Wax also supports his innate quest: the =20
continuous exploration of electronic music development.

Dettmann=E2=80=99s persistent reply to inquiries on his DJ-style =E2=80=93 n=
o doubts =20
about its foundational and just natural club-oriented functionality =E2=80=
=93 =20
simply and sparsely reads =E2=80=9Cdark=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe dark side=
=E2=80=9D. At a closer look =20
this brings to light a certain fascination in Techno: a futuristic =20
medium inherently pointing towards the new and unseen, unexplored and =20
unknown, undefined and unexpected.

For Dettmann Techno depicts a determination of both his life and =20
music. At the same time it opens up the needed space to develop =20
thoughts, actions and creations. Eventually Dettmann is having only =20
this space in mind: Berlin, Berghain, the Club. Marcel Dettmann is one =20
of the local residents of the Berlin club Berghain. He also runs the =20
label Marcel Dettman Records.

http://www.myspace.com/marceldettmann

Tracklist:
01. Dettmann / Klock =E2=80=93 Places Like This =E2=80=93 OstGut Ton 011
02. Scaff =E2=80=93 SSM 440 =E2=80=93 Kontra Musik 006
03. Adam Marshall =E2=80=93 Kokane - New Kanada 010
04. MD III =E2=80=93 Set Me Free =E2=80=93 Underground 111

Dear Moksha Tribe Supporters,

 
All of us in Moksha Tribe would like to thank you so much for joining us in our celebration of resurrection and new life at Phoenix, this last March 29th. We were so happy to see so many old friends, and to meet so many new ones. 


We are always thankful for the many genuine words and gestures of support we get from our guests before, during, and after our parties, but the truth is, YOU guys are what allow us to create a fabulous vibe at our parties. There is no way on earth to throw a loving, beautiful, and creative party, without loving, beautiful, and creative people coming out to join and support you. 


At Phoenix, your attendance didnt just help us throw a party to remember, but your incredible generosity allowed us to raise over 1,900 dollars for Larkin Street. 


We would like to take this time to publicly thank all the vendors, DJ's, and crew who helped us throw such a great party for love and not profit; we also could not have done it without them. 


If you enjoyed our party, or even if you just heard about it, and want to make sure you get all the future news and announcements from Moksha Tribe, make sure to sign up for our announce list at http://phoenix.mokshatribe.net, if you have not already. If you want to help out at our next party by working a shift, the announce list is also for you, we do throw out periodic calls for help to any who may be interested. 


Because our parties are all about YOU, our guests, we are very interested in your input. If you have any comments about Phoenix or suggestions for how to make our future parties even better, we encourage you to contact us at Sheztek@mokshatribe.net or to contact any of your friends in Moksha Tribe. 


Love and Respect, Moksha Tribe 



--0-1240350885-1210788721=:55113--

Bill Brewster's new newsletter.

> MAY NEWSLETTER
>
>
> The sun is out. You could almost be forgiven for thinking summer is =20=

> here. So we=92d thought we=92d launch our newsletter with an acid =
house =20
> special. Anything the Observer can do we can do better. In tribute =20
> I=92m currently sporting a haircut somewhere between Danny Rampling =20=

> and Lord Byron (Acid House Militia, Poetry Division).
>
> What with it being twenty years ago and all this Nu-Rave malarkey, =20
> its influence is around us like air and, er, hay fever. Fab For's =20
> Last Night A DJ Blew My Mind, a criminally overlooked acid-laden =20
> monster featuring Robert Owens, being one example, along with Tiga's =20=

> visceral Pleasure =46rom The Bass which also channels the spirit of =20=

> silly haircuts and Smiley badges in an effective manner. For the =20
> gothic Summer of Love sound look no further than Richard Sen=92s =20
> recent Padded Cell project, for whom the best example is Savage =20
> Skulls, a cross between Bauhaus and acid house. Just a few of many =20
> examples. There=92s also Foolish Felix=92s recent remix of =
Cro-Magnon=92s =20
> Take Me Higher which is pure 303 tomfoolery. It=92s not out yet, =20
> though. Sometimes you gotta keep something for yourself.
>
> The purpose of this missive is to let you know what=92s new on =20
> DJHistory - features, interviews, books, designer egg cups - as well =20=

> as throwing a few charts your way, the occasional free edit or mix, =20=

> competition giveaways and, of course, the best haggis recipes. Feel =20=

> free to forward to a friend. Or your mum.
> Bill Brewster
>
>
>
> NEW IN INTERVIEWS
> Danny Rampling
> One of the architects of acid house, recently out of retirement =20
> after three years of Rampling=92s Kitchen Nightmares.
> Froggy
> Pioneer UK mixing DJ, who tragically passed away in March.
>
> NEW IN FEATURES
> The Amnesiacs by John Godfrey
> Originally published in i-D in early 1988 and hilariously full of =20
> sly allusions to drug taking.
>
> House =9288 - Paradise Glimpsed by Louise Gray
> Louise Gray=92s end of year reflection perfectly captured the =20
> tumultuous events of 1988.
>
> NEW BOOK REVIEWS
> The Ha=E7ienda Must Be Built =96 Jon Savage (ed.)
> Manc=92s glory hole gets the completist treatment
>
> 24 Hour Party People =96 Tony Wilson
> Wilson=92s hilarious hit and myth memoir
>
> The Look: New Romantics =96 Dave Rimmer
> The substance behind the foundation
>
> LIQUID LIQUID COMPETITION COMPETITION
> Those generous folks at Domino Records have given us three VINYL =20
> copies of the highly prized new Liquid Liquid compilation Slip In =20
> and Out Of Phenomenon. It includes all their classic recordings =20
> alongside some excellent (and previously unreleased) live recordings =20=

> from back in the day. Worth 25 smackers in the shops, but free to =20
> you. The first three entries to answer the following question =20
> correctly get the prize.
>
> QUESTION: Who was the owner of Liquid Liquid label 99 Records? Email =20=

> the answer.

hot.

> Shoom regular.

> produced.

> The thin man of acid house serves up some delirium.

> Deliriously good northern rave monkey anthem. Now harder to find.
>

> Pam Hogg and loads of her batty mates serve up leftfield house.
>

> Jon Da Silva=92s mix was Ha=E7 anthem.

> Whatever happened to Simon Law?

The rag was soaked rapidly. Water flowed everywhere: in my mouth, in
my nose, all over my face. But for a while I could still breathe in
some small gulps of air. I tried, by contracting my throat, to take in
as little water as possible and to resist suffocation by keeping air
in my lungs for as long as I could. But I couldn't hold on for more
than a few moments. I had the impression of drowning, and a terrible
agony, that of death itself, took possession of me. In spite of
myself, all the muscles of my body struggled uselessly to save me from
suffocation. In spite of myself, the fingers of both my hands shook
uncontrollably. 'That's it! He's going to talk,' said a voice.

The water stopped running and they took away the rag. I was able to
breathe. In the gloom, I saw the lieutenants and the captain, who,
with a cigarette between his lips, was hitting my stomach with his
fist to make me throw out the water I had swallowed.

- Henri Alleg, The Question

Long one.  Well, enjoy.

--

I know a lot of you in the corporate world, a lot of you in society
have learned very young to follow the leader, you'll go up the ladder,
pose, act like a member of the establishment, always take the safe
course, never stick your neck out, never say anything the media has
said is kooky, don't be involved, don't talk about politics and
religion, just play ball and you will get ahead.

And I'm asking those people who have "played it safe" to count the
cost and realize that society is hurtling toward disaster and in so
many ways is experiencing ongoing disasters on a daily basis.  And I'm
asking you not to just poo-poo what we say here, but to really go and
look at the claims that we make here.  Even if you don't believe me,
why don't you want to disprove me?  Why don't you want to go out and
prove that I am a liar?

Because you're going to find out I'm not a liar.  And you're afraid to
go check out the claims I make and the things I say, because if you
do, then you will feel morally obligated to do something.  At least
many of you that still are moral individuals.

There are other people I've run into in society and emails calls I've
gotten and friends I've talked to whose family members have said
things like ... you say to them, "look at the Third World.  Look at
China and all the toxic waste and the massive health problems they're
having and cancer and all that," and they'll just giggle and say,
"well how does that affect me?"  And they somehow think that by not
caring about society, by not caring about their own environment, I
mean sociologically as much as biologically, that somehow they get
ahead.  And that by giggling, and being cynical, and snickering, and
by laughing at serious issues that somehow you have power over them.

What you have is a society collapsing, a society unraveling, a society
falling apart, first in slow-motion, and now in fast-motion, because
other people have a "so what" attitude.  So when bad things are
happening to you, or when bad drugs by big pharma are hurting you, or
when your child gets brain damaged by mercury in the vaccines,
nobody's going to care about you.  Or when your rights are violated at
a federally funded checkpoint on a highway, nobody's going to care
about you.

And that's really the message I wanted to put out today ...

- Alex Jones, Sunday, January 27, 2008 ~ 27 minutes

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Green Velvet this Saturday

------=_Part_3670_12539117.1210889747319
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

Heya everypeoples,
Just wanted to give a heads up (in case you don't know already) that we are
bringing Green Velvet to SF this Saturday at Temple Nightclub.

http://www.going.com/gvtemple  is where full info & tickets can be had.
 Press release below.  :)

Hope you can make it!

Few artists have the ability to produce timeless music that can cross genre
barriers and be enjoyed by listeners with diverse musical interests.   Green
Velvet is one of these few.

Producing under the Green Velvet moniker as well as his alter ego Cajmere,
Curtis A. Jones has released a steady stream of dance floor aimed tracks
since 1991.   His discography boasts many impressive contributions to dance
music: Flash, Answering Machine, (It's Time For) The Percolator, La La Land,
Shake & Pop and many others.

Curtis' ear for great music put him at the forefront of two seminal labels
in Chicago: Cajual Records and Relief Records.   These labels hosted his
original works as well as other renowned artists such as Armand Van Helden,
DJ Sneak, Dajae, Johnny Fiasco, Roy Davis Jr., Mark Grant, Gene Farris and
more. Green Velvet is usually found traveling across the globe to perform at
festivals and huge clubs but May 17th he will make a rare West Coast
appearance at San Francisco's Temple Nightclub, playing a DJ set while
singing some of his original works.

Rock It Science founder and local favorite Eric Sharp will open for Green
Velvet in the Main Room.   The Destiny Lounge will be hosted by Lights Down
Low and will feature Dirtybird Records' rising star Worthy as well as Lights
Down Low residents Sleazemore and Rchrd Oh!? along with Green Gorilla
Lounge's Jimmy B.   Photographers Bennett Sell-Kline and Parker Day will be
on hand to document the evening.  Temple's Hip Hop residents Bling Crosby
and 24K will hold it down in the Catacombs.

------=_Part_3670_12539117.1210889747319--

> Heya everypeoples,
> Just wanted to give a heads up (in case you don't know already) that we 
> are
> bringing Green Velvet to SF this Saturday at Temple Nightclub.
>
> http://www.going.com/gvtemple  is where full info & tickets can be had.
> Press release below.  :)
>
> Hope you can make it!
>
> Few artists have the ability to produce timeless music that can cross 
> genre
> barriers and be enjoyed by listeners with diverse musical interests. 
> Green
> Velvet is one of these few.
>
> Producing under the Green Velvet moniker as well as his alter ego Cajmere,
> Curtis A. Jones has released a steady stream of dance floor aimed tracks
> since 1991.   His discography boasts many impressive contributions to 
> dance
> music: Flash, Answering Machine, (It's Time For) The Percolator, La La 
> Land,
> Shake & Pop and many others.
>
> Curtis' ear for great music put him at the forefront of two seminal labels
> in Chicago: Cajual Records and Relief Records.   These labels hosted his
> original works as well as other renowned artists such as Armand Van 
> Helden,
> DJ Sneak, Dajae, Johnny Fiasco, Roy Davis Jr., Mark Grant, Gene Farris and
> more. Green Velvet is usually found traveling across the globe to perform 
> at
> festivals and huge clubs but May 17th he will make a rare West Coast
> appearance at San Francisco's Temple Nightclub, playing a DJ set while
> singing some of his original works.
>
> Rock It Science founder and local favorite Eric Sharp will open for Green
> Velvet in the Main Room.   The Destiny Lounge will be hosted by Lights 
> Down
> Low and will feature Dirtybird Records' rising star Worthy as well as 
> Lights
> Down Low residents Sleazemore and Rchrd Oh!? along with Green Gorilla
> Lounge's Jimmy B.   Photographers Bennett Sell-Kline and Parker Day will 
> be
> on hand to document the evening.  Temple's Hip Hop residents Bling Crosby
> and 24K will hold it down in the Catacombs.
>

Damages Will Take Many Years To Mend

Posted: May 14 2008

Please add us to your social network

Reddit      Digg      StumbleUpon      Yahoo! MyWeb
Del.icio.us      Technorati      Seed NewsVine
Rss Feed      FaceBook
What is this?
Poison from the top down, Fed is wrong to signal end of crisis, more =20
negative surprises in the markets to come, Mortgage market upside =20
down, major conflicts always a threat

I tremble for my country when I reflect that God is just; that his =20
justice cannot sleep forever.
Thomas Jefferson (1743-1826), Third President of the United States
I sought for the greatness and genius of America in her commodious =20
harbors and her ample rivers ? and it was not there ? in her fertile =20
fields and boundless forests ? and it was not there ? in her rich =20
mines and her vast world commerce ? and it was not there ? in her =20
democratic Congress and her matchless Constitution ? and it was not =20
there. Not until I went into the churches of America and heard her =20
pulpits flame with righteousness did I understand the secret of her =20
genius and power. America is great because she is good, and if America =20
ever ceases to be good, America will cease to be great.
Alexis De Tocqueville (1805-1859), French Lawyer, Political Thinker =20
and Historian

Our country is a disgrace.  It has been poisoned from the top down by =20
a cabal of men whose riches from the Industrial Revolution, coupled =20
with old money from Europe, corrupted their souls until there was =20
little more than a cesspool left within them.  As the poison has =20
spread, the people of our nation have done precious little to stop its =20
progress.  America has ceased to be good, and unless we change course =20
immediately, by whatever means are necessary, America will cease to be =20
great as predicted by De Tocqueville, and will come under the judgment =20
of our Creator as predicted by Jefferson.  We are a hair's breadth =20
from disaster, judgment and ignominy.  A vote for McCain, Obama or =20
Clinton will most certainly put us over the edge, while a vote for Ron =20
Paul would provide us with a change of course that could slingshot us =20
back to greatness and into the good graces of our Creator.
The ongoing corruption of America started to accelerate with the =20
concentration of vast sums of money into the hands of a few during the =20
Industrial Revolution.  People like Rothschild, Warburg, Rhodes, =20
Rockefeller, Carnegie, Morgan, Kennedy, Bush and Ford, some of whom =20
many people still venerate, were some of the most evil men of the late =20
nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.  They never gave a penny =20
without an agenda, and did not have a single altruistic bone in their =20
bodies.  That much money creates power, and, as Henry Kissinger once =20
said:  power corrupts, and absolute power corrupts absolutely.  He =20
should know.  The wealthy were lured into and became subservient to =20
the powers of darkness through various satanic and occult cabals, many =20
of which have been in existence in one form or another for thousands =20
of years.  For most of these industrial pirates, this was a very small =20
step since most of them were ruthless cutthroats to begin with.
The long line of exposure of debt problems by major and minor =20
corporate entities has a long way to go. The signals by the Fed, =20
Treasury and some corporate leaders that the credit crisis is over is =20
very misleading, as we see one corporation after another declare some =20
of their losses. From our vantage point we are nowhere out of the =20
woods. The credit healing process can be accomplished by admitting the =20
loss and writing them off and then rebuilding the balance sheet. =20
Unfortunately this won?t be easy in a recession and some companies =20
wont remain solvent. At the recent G7 meeting it was agreed that full =20
disclosure in the financial world would be quickly forthcoming. We?ll =20
believe it when we see it. After the tremendous losses by foreign =20
professional investors one can understand why there is little =20
confidence and trust left in the system.

We believe the financial sector will have many more negative surprises =20
as time passes. The financial markets supposedly have discounted =20
further adverse affects from the subprime/ALT-A fallout, but we think =20
there will be more big surprises then they have planned for. This =20
comfort zone is part of the reason the markets are trading as high as =20
they are. We wonder if they have also discounted the next five years? =20
pending problems in Option ARMs, those pick-and-pay loans? Have they =20
looked at the growing foreclosure rate in prime mortgages and are they =20
expecting another 15% to 25% fall in home prices in the former 30 hot =20
areas? We don?t think so. If markets believe the Fed will start =20
tightening later this year they are mistaken. Real interest rates will =20
rise, but not the Fed funds rate, nor the bank discount rate.

The shock to credit quality will take many years to mend. This isn?t =20
just a mortgage crisis; it is a systemic crisis. These financiers have =20
been looting the public for years and that game is over. The size of =20
the problems will have a multiplier effect, which will change the =20
credit markets for many years to come. One thing for sure is that =20
losses in all financial spheres will be far greater than imagined. As =20
far as housing is concerned inventories continue to build and will =20
continue to do so as prices continue falling. We are talking of =20
perhaps $2 trillion in losses. That is why official Fed interest rates =20
won?t rise for at least two years. Real market rates may rise, but =20
they are beyond the control of any one or group of central banks. In =20
the last six weeks the tone of the market has improved, but we look at =20
that slightly positive tone as transitory. The purge is on the way. =20
The Fed is extending it, but they can only do their magic for so long. =20
As we are seeing leveraged financial institutions are cutting down =20
leverage and lenders are only lending when the credit is pristine and =20
the profit is very large. This reduction of leverage and lending will =20
unfortunately magnify the effect to the downside. Eventually market =20
weakness will feed on itself. That has yet to happen, but it will =20
happen. We have a large drop in asset prices ahead of us, particularly =20
in real estate that will affect credit markets on an ongoing basis.

There is a lot more leverage in our housing market compared to prior =20
housing downturns in the US and worldwide. On a comparative basis the =20
leverage is about double most real estate markets since World War II. =20
In the former 30 hot areas we see 40% of homes in negative equity; =20
1/3rd of all homeowners own their homes free and clear, thus 27% would =20
have positive equity who have mortgages. That is $4.8 trillion =20
mortgages upside down. That is beyond the $2 trillion in problems that =20
already exist. If conditions deteriorate as much as we think they will =20
the collapse in the US economy could be devastating.

12-3/8% inflation is reality and it will be 15% before the year is =20
out. Finally the media is starting to pay attention, as is Congress. =20
Year-on-year worldwide food prices are up 57%, rice is up 125% and =20
wheat 65%. Oil prices have quadrupled since 9/11. At $125 a barrel the =20
bill for Americans is $300 billion. OPEC will increase revenues by =20
1/3rd to close to $1 trillion. Inflation is the product of the Fed?s =20
massive monetary aggregate creation and the wars and occupations in =20
Iraq and Afghanistan. The falling dollar is a product of both. We =20
believe that M3 creation has passed 18% over the past month with no =20
let up or end in sight. What is really a frightening possibility is =20
that our President may call for more ethanol to offset oil costs and =20
imports. If that happens food prices would rise ever higher causing =20
more inflation and death and starvation throughout the world. Already =20
about 20% of our corn crop goes into ethanol and in the coming crop =20
it?s supposed to be 30%, as Caligula and our corrupt Congress stands =20
by and does nothing. Worse yet, corn plantings could be off as much as =20
10%. That increase in ethanol is not going to keep oil from going to =20
$150.00 and gasoline from going to $5.00 a gallon. Our President?s =20
answer is to continue to put oil into the Petroleum Reserve and beg =20
Saudi Arabia for more production.

A subscriber in France recently reminded us that France?s Revolution =20
was all about bread. If food prices continue to spiral upward assisted =20
by energy prices we could have lynch mobs again out in force. You can =20
only fool and lie to the public for so long and eventually they =20
recognize how their President and Congress have corruptly deceived =20
them. They, the Fed, the banks, Wall Street and corporate America will =20
do anything to keep the Ponzi scheme alive. Were it not for foreign =20
central banks buying Treasuries and Agencies, America would have long =20
ago financially collapsed. In turn, the Fed buys any kind of toxic =20
junk thrown its way. The investment climate in the US is so poor =20
virtually no private foreign investment is entering the country. The =20
weak dollar, real estate problems and an unresolved credit crisis =20
doesn?t make investments very inviting.

The Fed tells us a net 55.4% of lenders tightened standards on =20
commercial and industrial loans to large and mid-sized customers in =20
the second quarter. That is up from 32.2% in the previous quarter and =20
minus 3.7% yoy. In commercial real estate 78.6% tightened standards, =20
in mortgages up from 52.9%. The Fed has tracked these numbers since =20
1991 and never previously has there been a reading over 32.7%.

In addition the percentage of lenders tightening standards on credit =20
card loans rose to 32.4% from 9.7%, the highest since 1997. All other =20
loans are 44.4% - the highest since data was collected in this =20
category in 1996.

This is an aggressive withdrawal of lenders from lending. Next we will =20
see a tightening in auto and other loans and credit cards. That =20
classification increased by $15.3 billion in March. Consumers took out =20
$34 billion in these loans during the first quarter, the most since =20
2001. That in part is because the house can no longer be used as an =20
ATM card. Then of course there is rampant inflation.

We are looking for another increase in real interest rates led by the =20
10-year Treasury note currently around 3.85%. The next move will be to =20
4.50%. That would put the 30-year fixed rate mortgage at 6.70% and put =20
jumbo loans at 7.65% to 9.65%. That should move us further into =20
recession and send the stock market down. A few of you have been =20
waiting for lower rates; we do not believe they are coming, so commit =20
yourselves now if you have a resetting loan. Bondholders are losing =20
money on official inflation rates. Based on our figures they are =20
getting decimated. We saw a crack in the Fed?s defense regarding =20
inflation last week when K. C. Fed President Thomas Hoenig said, =20
?There is significant risk that higher inflation will become embedded =20
in the economy and require significant monetary policy tightening to =20
reduce it.? If the Fed did that we?d have instant depression. This is =20
why the only bonds we recommend are Swiss franc government bonds.

Private investment firms have been amassing hundreds of apartment =20
buildings with thousands of rent-regulated units across the City of =20
New York have produced decidedly meager returns. What the investors =20
are doing is harassing the tenants repeatedly for unpaid rent that =20
landlords have already received; they are sent false rent bills, lease =20
terminations and non-renewals and they have been accused of illegal =20
sublets. This predatory equity is undermining affordable housing in NYC.

In the last four years these private equity firms have acquired 75,000 =20
rental regulated apartments, or 6% of 1.2 million of such units. The =20
idea is to get the rent over $2,000 a month, and the regulations no =20
longer apply. About 50% of units in the boroughs are rent controlled.

Evidentially not ready to attack Iran the US and UK have opted for a =20
softer target and perhaps a gateway to Iran. There is no question this =20
latest Middle East crisis is being orchestrated in Lebanon. We also =20
believe for reasons unknown to us that at the same time Lebanon is =20
heating up and so is Georgia and Kosovo and it looks like the =20
Illuminists are dumping the Clintons. It could be major conflicts are =20
going to break out almost simultaneously to cover up the economic and =20
financial collapse in the US, which will spread worldwide.

> Fed will start tightening later this year they are mistaken. Real interest
> rates will rise, but not the Fed funds rate, nor the bank discount rate.
>
> The shock to credit quality will take many years to mend. This isn?t just a
> mortgage crisis; it is a systemic crisis. These financiers have been looting
> the public for years and that game is over. The size of the problems will
> have a multiplier effect, which will change the credit markets for many
> years to come. One thing for sure is that losses in all financial spheres
> will be far greater than imagined. As far as housing is concerned
> inventories continue to build and will continue to do so as prices continue
> falling. We are talking of perhaps $2 trillion in losses. That is why
> official Fed interest rates won?t rise for at least two years. Real market
> rates may rise, but they are beyond the control of any one or group of
> central banks. In the last six weeks the tone of the market has improved,
> but we look at that slightly positive tone as transitory. The purge is on
> the way. The Fed is extending it, but they can only do their magic for so
> long. As we are seeing leveraged financial institutions are cutting down
> leverage and lenders are only lending when the credit is pristine and the
> profit is very large. This reduction of leverage and lending will
> unfortunately magnify the effect to the downside. Eventually market weakness
> will feed on itself. That has yet to happen, but it will happen. We have a
> large drop in asset prices ahead of us, particularly in real estate that
> will affect credit markets on an ongoing basis.
>
> There is a lot more leverage in our housing market compared to prior
> housing downturns in the US and worldwide. On a comparative basis the
> leverage is about double most real estate markets since World War II. In the
> former 30 hot areas we see 40% of homes in negative equity; 1/3rd of all
> homeowners own their homes free and clear, thus 27% would have positive
> equity who have mortgages. That is $4.8 trillion mortgages upside down. That
> is beyond the $2 trillion in problems that already exist. If conditions
> deteriorate as much as we think they will the collapse in the US economy
> could be devastating.
>
> 12-3/8% inflation is reality and it will be 15% before the year is out.
> Finally the media is starting to pay attention, as is Congress. Year-on-year
> worldwide food prices are up 57%, rice is up 125% and wheat 65%. Oil prices
> have quadrupled since 9/11. At $125 a barrel the bill for Americans is $300
> billion. OPEC will increase revenues by 1/3rd to close to $1 trillion.
> Inflation is the product of the Fed?s massive monetary aggregate creation
> and the wars and occupations in Iraq and Afghanistan. The falling dollar is
> a product of both. We believe that M3 creation has passed 18% over the past
> month with no let up or end in sight. What is really a frightening
> possibility is that our President may call for more ethanol to offset oil
> costs and imports. If that happens food prices would rise ever higher
> causing more inflation and death and starvation throughout the world.
> Already about 20% of our corn crop goes into ethanol and in the coming crop
> it?s supposed to be 30%, as Caligula and our corrupt Congress stands by and
> does nothing. Worse yet, corn plantings could be off as much as 10%. That
> increase in ethanol is not going to keep oil from going to $150.00 and
> gasoline from going to $5.00 a gallon. Our President?s answer is to continue
> to put oil into the Petroleum Reserve and beg Saudi Arabia for more
> production.
>
> A subscriber in France recently reminded us that France?s Revolution was
> all about bread. If food prices continue to spiral upward assisted by energy
> prices we could have lynch mobs again out in force. You can only fool and
> lie to the public for so long and eventually they recognize how their
> President and Congress have corruptly deceived them. They, the Fed, the
> banks, Wall Street and corporate America will do anything to keep the Ponzi
> scheme alive. Were it not for foreign central banks buying Treasuries and
> Agencies, America would have long ago financially collapsed. In turn, the
> Fed buys any kind of toxic junk thrown its way. The investment climate in
> the US is so poor virtually no private foreign investment is entering the
> country. The weak dollar, real estate problems and an unresolved credit
> crisis doesn?t make investments very inviting.
>
> The Fed tells us a net 55.4% of lenders tightened standards on commercial
> and industrial loans to large and mid-sized customers in the second quarter.
> That is up from 32.2% in the previous quarter and minus 3.7% yoy. In
> commercial real estate 78.6% tightened standards, in mortgages up from
> 52.9%. The Fed has tracked these numbers since 1991 and never previously has
> there been a reading over 32.7%.
>
> In addition the percentage of lenders tightening standards on credit card
> loans rose to 32.4% from 9.7%, the highest since 1997. All other loans are
> 44.4% - the highest since data was collected in this category in 1996.
>
> This is an aggressive withdrawal of lenders from lending. Next we will see
> a tightening in auto and other loans and credit cards. That classification
> increased by $15.3 billion in March. Consumers took out $34 billion in these
> loans during the first quarter, the most since 2001. That in part is because
> the house can no longer be used as an ATM card. Then of course there is
> rampant inflation.
>
> We are looking for another increase in real interest rates led by the
> 10-year Treasury note currently around 3.85%. The next move will be to
> 4.50%. That would put the 30-year fixed rate mortgage at 6.70% and put jumbo
> loans at 7.65% to 9.65%. That should move us further into recession and send
> the stock market down. A few of you have been waiting for lower rates; we do
> not believe they are coming, so commit yourselves now if you have a
> resetting loan. Bondholders are losing money on official inflation rates.
> Based on our figures they are getting decimated. We saw a crack in the Fed?s
> defense regarding inflation last week when K. C. Fed President Thomas Hoenig
> said, ?There is significant risk that higher inflation will become embedded
> in the economy and require significant monetary policy tightening to reduce
> it.? If the Fed did that we?d have instant depression. This is why the only
> bonds we recommend are Swiss franc government bonds.
>
> Private investment firms have been amassing hundreds of apartment buildings
> with thousands of rent-regulated units across the City of New York have
> produced decidedly meager returns. What the investors are doing is harassing
> the tenants repeatedly for unpaid rent that landlords have already received;
> they are sent false rent bills, lease terminations and non-renewals and they
> have been accused of illegal sublets. This predatory equity is undermining
> affordable housing in NYC.
>
> In the last four years these private equity firms have acquired 75,000
> rental regulated apartments, or 6% of 1.2 million of such units. The idea is
> to get the rent over $2,000 a month, and the regulations no longer apply.
> About 50% of units in the boroughs are rent controlled.

>> rates will rise, but not the Fed funds rate, nor the bank discount

>>

>> falling. We are talking of perhaps $2 trillion in losses. That is why

>> central banks. In the last six weeks the tone of the market has  
>> improved,

>> purge is on
>> the way. The Fed is extending it, but they can only do their magic  
>> for so
>> long. As we are seeing leveraged financial institutions are  
>> cutting down
>> leverage and lenders are only lending when the credit is pristine

>> commercial
>> and industrial loans to large and mid-sized customers in the  
>> second quarter.
>> That is up from 32.2% in the previous quarter and minus 3.7% yoy. In
>> commercial real estate 78.6% tightened standards, in mortgages up  
>> from
>> 52.9%. The Fed has tracked these numbers since 1991 and never  
>> previously has
>> there been a reading over 32.7%.
>>
>> In addition the percentage of lenders tightening standards on  
>> credit card
>> loans rose to 32.4% from 9.7%, the highest since 1997. All other  
>> loans are
>> 44.4% - the highest since data was collected in this category in  
>> 1996.
>>
>> This is an aggressive withdrawal of lenders from lending. Next we  
>> will see
>> a tightening in auto and other loans and credit cards. That  
>> classification
>> increased by $15.3 billion in March. Consumers took out $34  
>> billion in these
>> loans during the first quarter, the most since 2001. That in part  
>> is because
>> the house can no longer be used as an ATM card. Then of course  
>> there is
>> rampant inflation.

>> 4.50%. That would put the 30-year fixed rate mortgage at 6.70% and

>> loans at 7.65% to 9.65%. That should move us further into

>> the stock market down. A few of you have been waiting for lower

>> not believe they are coming, so commit yourselves now if you have a

>> rates.

>> in the economy and require significant monetary policy tightening

>>> housing downturns in the US and worldwide. On a comparative basis the
>>> leverage is about double most real estate markets since World War II. In
>>> the
>>> former 30 hot areas we see 40% of homes in negative equity; 1/3rd of all
>>> homeowners own their homes free and clear, thus 27% would have positive
>>> equity who have mortgages. That is $4.8 trillion mortgages upside down.
>>> That
>>> is beyond the $2 trillion in problems that already exist. If conditions
>>> deteriorate as much as we think they will the collapse in the US economy
>>> could be devastating.
>>>
>>> 12-3/8% inflation is reality and it will be 15% before the year is out.
>>> Finally the media is starting to pay attention, as is Congress.
>>> Year-on-year
>>> worldwide food prices are up 57%, rice is up 125% and wheat 65%. Oil
>>> prices
>>> have quadrupled since 9/11. At $125 a barrel the bill for Americans is
>>> $300
>>> billion. OPEC will increase revenues by 1/3rd to close to $1 trillion.
>>> Inflation is the product of the Fed?s massive monetary aggregate creation
>>> and the wars and occupations in Iraq and Afghanistan. The falling dollar
>>> is
>>> a product of both. We believe that M3 creation has passed 18% over the
>>> past
>>> month with no let up or end in sight. What is really a frightening
>>> possibility is that our President may call for more ethanol to offset oil
>>> costs and imports. If that happens food prices would rise ever higher
>>> causing more inflation and death and starvation throughout the world.
>>> Already about 20% of our corn crop goes into ethanol and in the coming
>>> crop
>>> it?s supposed to be 30%, as Caligula and our corrupt Congress stands by
>>> and
>>> does nothing. Worse yet, corn plantings could be off as much as 10%. That
>>> increase in ethanol is not going to keep oil from going to $150.00 and
>>> gasoline from going to $5.00 a gallon. Our President?s answer is to
>>> continue
>>> to put oil into the Petroleum Reserve and beg Saudi Arabia for more
>>> production.
>>>
>>> A subscriber in France recently reminded us that France?s Revolution was
>>> all about bread. If food prices continue to spiral upward assisted by
>>> energy
>>> prices we could have lynch mobs again out in force. You can only fool and
>>> lie to the public for so long and eventually they recognize how their
>>> President and Congress have corruptly deceived them. They, the Fed, the
>>> banks, Wall Street and corporate America will do anything to keep the
>>> Ponzi
>>> scheme alive. Were it not for foreign central banks buying Treasuries and
>>> Agencies, America would have long ago financially collapsed. In turn, the
>>> Fed buys any kind of toxic junk thrown its way. The investment climate in
>>> the US is so poor virtually no private foreign investment is entering the
>>> country. The weak dollar, real estate problems and an unresolved credit
>>> crisis doesn?t make investments very inviting.
>>>
>>> The Fed tells us a net 55.4% of lenders tightened standards on commercial
>>> and industrial loans to large and mid-sized customers in the second
>>> quarter.
>>> That is up from 32.2% in the previous quarter and minus 3.7% yoy. In
>>> commercial real estate 78.6% tightened standards, in mortgages up from
>>> 52.9%. The Fed has tracked these numbers since 1991 and never previously
>>> has
>>> there been a reading over 32.7%.
>>>
>>> In addition the percentage of lenders tightening standards on credit card
>>> loans rose to 32.4% from 9.7%, the highest since 1997. All other loans
>>> are
>>> 44.4% - the highest since data was collected in this category in 1996.
>>>
>>> This is an aggressive withdrawal of lenders from lending. Next we will
>>> see
>>> a tightening in auto and other loans and credit cards. That
>>> classification
>>> increased by $15.3 billion in March. Consumers took out $34 billion in
>>> these
>>> loans during the first quarter, the most since 2001. That in part is
>>> because
>>> the house can no longer be used as an ATM card. Then of course there is
>>> rampant inflation.
>>>
>>> We are looking for another increase in real interest rates led by the
>>> 10-year Treasury note currently around 3.85%. The next move will be to
>>> 4.50%. That would put the 30-year fixed rate mortgage at 6.70% and put
>>> jumbo
>>> loans at 7.65% to 9.65%. That should move us further into recession and
>>> send
>>> the stock market down. A few of you have been waiting for lower rates; we
>>> do
>>> not believe they are coming, so commit yourselves now if you have a
>>> resetting loan. Bondholders are losing money on official inflation rates.
>>> Based on our figures they are getting decimated. We saw a crack in the
>>> Fed?s
>>> defense regarding inflation last week when K. C. Fed President Thomas
>>> Hoenig
>>> said, ?There is significant risk that higher inflation will become
>>> embedded
>>> in the economy and require significant monetary policy tightening to
>>> reduce
>>> it.? If the Fed did that we?d have instant depression. This is why the
>>> only
>>> bonds we recommend are Swiss franc government bonds.
>>>
>>> Private investment firms have been amassing hundreds of apartment
>>> buildings
>>> with thousands of rent-regulated units across the City of New York have
>>> produced decidedly meager returns. What the investors are doing is
>>> harassing
>>> the tenants repeatedly for unpaid rent that landlords have already
>>> received;
>>> they are sent false rent bills, lease terminations and non-renewals and
>>> they
>>> have been accused of illegal sublets. This predatory equity is
>>> undermining
>>> affordable housing in NYC.
>>>
>>> In the last four years these private equity firms have acquired 75,000
>>> rental regulated apartments, or 6% of 1.2 million of such units. The idea
>>> is
>>> to get the rent over $2,000 a month, and the regulations no longer apply.
>>> About 50% of units in the boroughs are rent controlled.
>>>
>>> Evidentially not ready to attack Iran the US and UK have opted for a
>>> softer

>>> Georgia and Kosovo and it looks like the Illuminists are dumping the

Black Market always put on quality shows.

Past guests have included Todd Sines, Sassmouth, Josh Dahlberg, Drew Pompa,
Rich Korach, Limacon, Andre Lucero, Monty Luke, Christian Martin, Alland
Byallo, Monocle, and plenty more.

I think this is their first all day thing, but the last all day BBQ there
(hosted by the 4 tuesday techno crews @ 222) was an absolute hoot!

Great outdoor venue, fun lineup, thumpy soundsystem, grillin', and FREE?

No brainer.  ESPECIALLY if you live in Oaktown.

------>GB

of parties, learned to be grumpy and say "No" and "well I'll give you a

course I check out the specs...

"We admitted we were powerless over our addiction - that our lives had 
become unmanageable"

some of our favorite mixes of all time from Frankie Bones, DJ Misjah &
Speedy J.  Right now we're playing some classic tracks that still inspire us

 http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

This week on Radio Integrated /// Friday, May 16th 2008 ///
http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

Tonight Radio Integrated is going to take it easy, maybe not do as many
tequila shots as usual, and sit back and listen to some of our favorite
mixes and tracks for our Influences & History show. We'll be playing classic
mixes from DJ Misjah, Speedy J, Frankie Bones, as well as tracks that
influenced and inspired us in the early days of our music careers.


Tune in at :

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/

Every Friday from 9pm - 1am Pacific Time

Contact : radiointegrated@gmail.com  www.myspace.com/radiointegrated

news and info, sign up for the DEF list at
def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com

For Radio Integrated updates:
radio-integrated-subscribe@defsf.com

Subject: Re: [sfraves] ambient mafia vs. ambient evil robot army

my bad.  i found the e-mails, i was wrong.  obviously i've
forgotten about the whole deal.  it wasn't as simple as us
refusing you entry, tho.  but if you'd like to break it down
that way, okay.  i'm fine with your interpretation.

glad you're doing ambient on your own.  in reality, the ambient
mafia doesn't really spin ambient much anymore (more to my
dismay).  this isn't due to lack of interest on our part, it's
more the evolution of the rave scene.

as you know, the mafia was formed during the days of the
massive, when there were 5 rooms per venue, when you could get
a nice variety of music at any given time.  these days, we're
lucky if there's two or three rooms.  the promoters we've
worked with haven't been looking for ambient, unfortunately.

thus, the formula we've found for success has involved a shift
away from "ambient" and more of a focus on downtempo.  we did
have an ambient room at the 8-year, and are planning on doing
some ambient at a campout in the near future.

props to you for bringing it back, and doing so with style.

good luck and stuff - i'd love to see your setup in action.

m

Subject: RE: [sfraves] ambient mafia vs. ambient evil robot army

sort of correct.

i consider downtempo to be anything from 60BPM (a lot of dub
falls into this category) up thru 110BPM (some may place the
delimiter lower).  105-110 thru 120BPM i classify as midtempo.

nico, you should know better - there's always ishkur.
http://techno.org/electronic-music-guide/

m

Content-type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII; format=flowed; delsp=yes
Content-transfer-encoding: 7BIT


it's a full moon this Tuesday..

and believe it or not it's also just over 17 years since our first  
wicked full moon out on Baker Beach. Those wild & nomadic gatherings  
may have only lasted about 5 years, but they inspired a whole lot of  
other folks to get involved in the dance music world, from the many  
other West Coast full moon parties that followed in our wake, to the  
still going 'Sunset' parties here in the Bay Area, to the many  
musicians, dj's and artists who gathered together under the moon's  
glow and let the psychedelic and revolutionary nature of those  
beautiful nights seep into their creative output..

We may have all moved on from those heady days, and the music has most  
definitely mutated over the years, but the spirit still remains. As it  
will long after people are gone from this planet. So join us for some  
full moon magick this Tuesday 9-2am in the VOID..

go to 90hz.org to listen and chat



Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

it's a full moon this Tuesday..

and believe it or not it's also just over 17 years since our first  
wicked full moon out on Baker Beach. Those wild & nomadic gatherings  
may have only lasted about 5 years, but they inspired a whole lot of  
other folks to get involved in the dance music world, from the many  
other West Coast full moon parties that followed in our wake, to the  
still going 'Sunset' parties here in the Bay Area, to the many  
musicians, dj's and artists who gathered together under the moon's  
glow and let the psychedelic and revolutionary nature of those  
beautiful nights seep into their creative output..

We may have all moved on from those heady days, and the music has most  
definitely mutated over the years, but the spirit still remains. As it  
will long after people are gone from this planet. So join us for some  
full moon magick this Tuesday 9-2am in the VOID..

British techno pioneer James Ruskin is a resident at Berlin's Tresor =20
club and responsible for the latest Tresor Album, Tresor 233 - The =20
Dash. He also runs his own label Blueprint. If you happen to be in =20
Detroit Michigan next Sunday you can catch him at the Substance after =20
party.

http://wrhaw.com/audio/James%20Ruskin/James_Ruskin_@_Techno_Vision_08-03-200=
8-_-www.toxic-culture.org.mp3

James Ruskin's Biography

Growing up in London and New Milton, Hampshire James Ruskin caught the =20
HIp-Hop bug through the likes of the Tim Westwood radio show and the =20
Electro Series on Street Sounds at an early age. When House started =20
seeping into the more progressive nightclubs James started to take =20
note of this new and infectious groove. Via the gravitational =20
slingshot of a Motor City sonic shockwave, the sound of Techno swept =20
him off his feet and has remained ever since.

Inspired by these new pioneering sounds James took up DJing and =20
eventually secured club bookings. With like minded friend, Richard =20
Polson, he relocated to London in 1994 and began building a new studio.

Conscious of developing their own sound the pair worked on material =20
for the next two years, releasing an EP on Guilty Records as 'Void' =20
until they were confident enough to release a four track EP that =20
captured their own style. 'First Contact' by Outline became their =20
first release on 'Ruskin's' label, Blueprint Records in May 1996.

With the label gaining momentum James's DJ bookings started to take =20
off. Resident at Gecko, London with Bloodsugar's Rick Hopkins he also =20
began taking bookings all over the UK and Europe. His DJ roster now =20
reads like a well established CV. His DJing has been witnessed at =20
House of God (Birmingham), Black Out (Glasgow), EuroBeat 2000 =20
(London), Attack (Reading), U-Club (Slovakia), The Complex (London), =20
The Liquid Rooms (Tokyo), Club Rockets (Osaka), Atomic Jam =20
(Birmingham), Geushky (Portsmouth), Dynamic Tension @ Tresor (Berlin), =20
Fusion (Nottingham), Ultraschall (Munich), Hurytan (Slovakia), and =20
Amorphous (Leicester), Lakota (Bristol), a bi-monthly residency @ =20
Tresor (Berlin), Chicago, New York, Detroit, Bugged Out (Manchester), =20
Art Futura (Madrid), Barcelona, Voodoo (Liverpool), Budapest, Berlin =20
Love Parade, Malta, Dublin (Kitchen) and a monthly residency with =20
Andrew Weatherall @ Circulation (London).

With Blueprint Records gathering respect the world over, his debut =20
album 'Further Design' released on 20th July, 1998 has propelled his =20
status as one of the UK techno scenes leading lights. His records are =20
being played by the likes of Jeff Mills, Dave Clarke, Suregeon, Andrew =20
Weatherall, Claude Young, Fumiya Tanaka, Steve Bicknell and many other =20
techno DJs. Select magazine quoted in their October 1997 edition: =20
'Blueprint Records. The best techno in ages. and it's British'.

Favourite Labels
Surface
Dynamic Tension
Meta
Downwards

Purpose Maker
Ground
Cosmic

Favourite Techno DJ's
Surgeon

Oliver Ho

he's ready to party hard! DIRTYHERTZ, along with DJ GUNZ and Misha
Kouznetsov are gonna' rock hard on the decks this Wednesday, 5/21 @
Shine. DeTension has built quite a reputation for the best new place to
party on Wednesday nights, and this week's edition surely isn't going
to hurt that rep any! In addition to the incredible lineup, there'll be
2-for-1 vodka drinks all night, a free Flickr photo booth in the back,
a fabulous stock of party people, and it's all FREE.=20

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: CaliGrown in the HOUSE on An Epiphany Of Sound tomorrow

I've been looking forward to this week's show for a while now, as I'll 
be featuring a solid 3 hr show with solid CaliGrown DJs.  We'll be 
featuring CaliGrown DJ's: Chuck.G, Dean Kroh, and Hil Huerta from 
9a-noon this Thur!  It'll be guaranteed to cover the House music you 
want to hear.

We're on from 9a-noon, following The Eklectronic Groove from 6a-9a, so 
you've actually got a 6 hour block of beats to satisfy.

If you're in the listening range of KZSU, tune in to 90.1 FM.  If you're 
not, search for KZSU in iTunes, or head over to 
http://kzsulive.stanford.edu

Do NOT sleep on this one!

Here's more about the DJs:

DJ Hil Huerta (CaliGrown, Skillz, OPPSF) was introduced to club music in 
the early 80's by his cousin, Eddie Garcia (aka Eddie Def).  He began 
DJing on a set of used decks when he was 11 years old. By 1986, while 
still in middle school, Hil had begun throwing and promoting parties, 
playing a mix of freestyle, hip hop, and early house music. Hil's drive 
and love of dance music has not abated.  Now one of the Bay Area's top 
promoters and still a top-notch DJ, Hil is know for his eclectic house 
music sets, ranging from funky cuts to electro-fueled tech house to 
progressive grooves.  Of course, says Hil, "I still have all of my old 
stuff, so you never know when I might throw in something classic."

Of course, all of this musical diversity serves a purpose.  While some 
DJ's will play a singular type of music to a crowd that's not enjoying 
it, Hil has a deeper appreciation for dancers and wants to make sure 
everyone has a good time.  As he says "I play every level of house 
music, just to keep the crowd moving." In his continuing quest to keep 
the crowd moving, Hil divides his time between DJing, running a 
successful promotions company, and work in the studio.  He is currently 
producing music with Homero Espinosa of Yerba Buena Discos.

DJ Hil's notable residences & bookings include Club 1015 (SF), Space 550 
(SF), Ultra Music Festival (Miami); Lovefest (and "Love" in SF).

Chuck.G, co-founder of CaliGrown Events, first learned to DJ in Dean's 
garage over 10 years ago. Although he hasn't pursued DJ'ing as a 
full-time career, music has been a lifelong passion for Chuck. He sums 
up this passion with the following statement: "My first rave was in 
Germany, during a High School exchange visit in the 'early' 90's.  I 
walked in, and that was it."

Chuck's passion for music has driven him to DJ, produce, and promote 
underground music events under different names & aliases his entire 
adult life. Chuck's more notable gigs include opening for Filter Grinder 
(Bush Records) in North Hollywood in 2002, and a residennce at the now 
infamous Club Ibiza in 2001, being billed with such acts as DJ Keoki, 
Dirty Vegas, and even MTV's DJ Scribble (Although Chuck jokes about how 
small his name was in print, and how the first time he was mistakenly 
billed as DJ "G-huck.G"- a name that has stuck with his friends). 
Although Chuck claims he sold his soul to House, he is never afraid to 
step outside of the box and drop some raw sh!t. Therefore, he classifies 
himself as a "party DJ" instead of limiting his scope to one genre.

DJ Dean Kroh (CaliGrown, Seedling Music, Liquid Graf-X) is one mean 
breaks DJ. Hailing from Stockton (holla!) Dean's been rocking dance 
floors since 1996 with some raw tracks you ain't never heard! With too 
many notable gigs to list, let's just say he's been doin' this since 
HomeBase was a Nu-skool spot, ya heard!?!?

So that's what to expect!  Hope to have you listening!


-- 
San Francisco Bay Guardian's Readers Choice Award Winner: Best Radio DJ:
http://www.sfbg.com/promo/pollpositions.php
AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)

"Opinions are my own only, and do not necessarily represent those of
KZSU Radio or Stanford University." (or words to that effect.)

----- Original Message ----
From: J.C. <dougm@kzsu.stanford.edu>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Wednesday, May 21, 2008 4:46:38 PM
Subject: [sfraves] BSP: CaliGrown in the HOUSE on An Epiphany Of Sound tomorrow

I've been looking forward to this week's show for a while now, as I'll 
be featuring a solid 3 hr show with solid CaliGrown DJs.  We'll be 
featuring CaliGrown DJ's: Chuck.G, Dean Kroh, and Hil Huerta from 
9a-noon this Thur!  It'll be guaranteed to cover the House music you 
want to hear.

We're on from 9a-noon, following The Eklectronic Groove from 6a-9a, so 
you've actually got a 6 hour block of beats to satisfy.

If you're in the listening range of KZSU, tune in to 90.1 FM.  If you're 
not, search for KZSU in iTunes, or head over to 
http://kzsulive.stanford.edu

Do NOT sleep on this one!

Here's more about the DJs:

DJ Hil Huerta (CaliGrown, Skillz, OPPSF) was introduced to club music in 
the early 80's by his cousin, Eddie Garcia (aka Eddie Def).  He began 
DJing on a set of used decks when he was 11 years old. By 1986, while 
still in middle school, Hil had begun throwing and promoting parties, 
playing a mix of freestyle, hip hop, and early house music. Hil's drive 
and love of dance music has not abated.  Now one of the Bay Area's top 
promoters and still a top-notch DJ, Hil is know for his eclectic house 
music sets, ranging from funky cuts to electro-fueled tech house to 
progressive grooves.  Of course, says Hil, "I still have all of my old 
stuff, so you never know when I might throw in something classic."

Of course, all of this musical diversity serves a purpose.  While some 
DJ's will play a singular type of music to a crowd that's not enjoying 
it, Hil has a deeper appreciation for dancers and wants to make sure 
everyone has a good time.  As he says "I play every level of house 
music, just to keep the crowd moving." In his continuing quest to keep 
the crowd moving, Hil divides his time between DJing, running a 
successful promotions company, and work in the studio.  He is currently 
producing music with Homero Espinosa of Yerba Buena Discos.

DJ Hil's notable residences & bookings include Club 1015 (SF), Space 550 
(SF), Ultra Music Festival (Miami); Lovefest (and "Love" in SF).

Chuck.G, co-founder of CaliGrown Events, first learned to DJ in Dean's 
garage over 10 years ago. Although he hasn't pursued DJ'ing as a 
full-time career, music has been a lifelong passion for Chuck. He sums 
up this passion with the following statement: "My first rave was in 
Germany, during a High School exchange visit in the 'early' 90's.  I 
walked in, and that was it."

Chuck's passion for music has driven him to DJ, produce, and promote 
underground music events under different names & aliases his entire 
adult life. Chuck's more notable gigs include opening for Filter Grinder 
(Bush Records) in North Hollywood in 2002, and a residennce at the now 
infamous Club Ibiza in 2001, being billed with such acts as DJ Keoki, 
Dirty Vegas, and even MTV's DJ Scribble (Although Chuck jokes about how 
small his name was in print, and how the first time he was mistakenly 
billed as DJ "G-huck.G"- a name that has stuck with his friends). 
Although Chuck claims he sold his soul to House, he is never afraid to 
step outside of the box and drop some raw sh!t. Therefore, he classifies 
himself as a "party DJ" instead of limiting his scope to one genre.

DJ Dean Kroh (CaliGrown, Seedling Music, Liquid Graf-X) is one mean 
breaks DJ. Hailing from Stockton (holla!) Dean's been rocking dance 
floors since 1996 with some raw tracks you ain't never heard! With too 
many notable gigs to list, let's just say he's been doin' this since 
HomeBase was a Nu-skool spot, ya heard!?!?

So that's what to expect!  Hope to have you listening!


-- 
San Francisco Bay Guardian's Readers Choice Award Winner: Best Radio DJ:
http://www.sfbg.com/promo/pollpositions.php
AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)

"Opinions are my own only, and do not necessarily represent those of
KZSU Radio or Stanford University." (or words to that effect.)

> I've been looking forward to this week's show for a
> while now, as I'll 
> be featuring a solid 3 hr show with solid CaliGrown DJs. 
> We'll be 
> featuring CaliGrown DJ's: Chuck.G, Dean Kroh, and Hil
> Huerta from 
> 9a-noon this Thur!  It'll be guaranteed to cover the
> House music you 
> want to hear.
> 
> We're on from 9a-noon, following The Eklectronic Groove
> from 6a-9a, so 
> you've actually got a 6 hour block of beats to satisfy.
> 
> If you're in the listening range of KZSU, tune in to
> 90.1 FM.  If you're 
> not, search for KZSU in iTunes, or head over to 
> http://kzsulive.stanford.edu
> 
> Do NOT sleep on this one!
> 
> Here's more about the DJs:
> 
> DJ Hil Huerta (CaliGrown, Skillz, OPPSF) was introduced to
> club music in 
> the early 80's by his cousin, Eddie Garcia (aka Eddie
> Def).  He began 
> DJing on a set of used decks when he was 11 years old. By
> 1986, while 
> still in middle school, Hil had begun throwing and
> promoting parties, 
> playing a mix of freestyle, hip hop, and early house music.
> Hil's drive 
> and love of dance music has not abated.  Now one of the Bay
> Area's top 
> promoters and still a top-notch DJ, Hil is know for his
> eclectic house 
> music sets, ranging from funky cuts to electro-fueled tech
> house to 
> progressive grooves.  Of course, says Hil, "I still
> have all of my old 
> stuff, so you never know when I might throw in something
> classic."
> 
> Of course, all of this musical diversity serves a purpose. 
> While some 
> DJ's will play a singular type of music to a crowd
> that's not enjoying 
> it, Hil has a deeper appreciation for dancers and wants to
> make sure 
> everyone has a good time.  As he says "I play every
> level of house 
> music, just to keep the crowd moving." In his
> continuing quest to keep 
> the crowd moving, Hil divides his time between DJing,
> running a 
> successful promotions company, and work in the studio.  He
> is currently 
> producing music with Homero Espinosa of Yerba Buena Discos.
> 
> DJ Hil's notable residences & bookings include Club
> 1015 (SF), Space 550 
> (SF), Ultra Music Festival (Miami); Lovefest (and
> "Love" in SF).
> 
> Chuck.G, co-founder of CaliGrown Events, first learned to
> DJ in Dean's 
> garage over 10 years ago. Although he hasn't pursued
> DJ'ing as a 
> full-time career, music has been a lifelong passion for
> Chuck. He sums 
> up this passion with the following statement: "My
> first rave was in 
> Germany, during a High School exchange visit in the
> 'early' 90's.  I 
> walked in, and that was it."
> 
> Chuck's passion for music has driven him to DJ,
> produce, and promote 
> underground music events under different names &
> aliases his entire 
> adult life. Chuck's more notable gigs include opening
> for Filter Grinder 
> (Bush Records) in North Hollywood in 2002, and a residennce
> at the now 
> infamous Club Ibiza in 2001, being billed with such acts as
> DJ Keoki, 
> Dirty Vegas, and even MTV's DJ Scribble (Although Chuck
> jokes about how 
> small his name was in print, and how the first time he was
> mistakenly 
> billed as DJ "G-huck.G"- a name that has stuck
> with his friends). 
> Although Chuck claims he sold his soul to House, he is
> never afraid to 
> step outside of the box and drop some raw sh!t. Therefore,
> he classifies 
> himself as a "party DJ" instead of limiting his
> scope to one genre.
> 
> DJ Dean Kroh (CaliGrown, Seedling Music, Liquid Graf-X) is
> one mean 
> breaks DJ. Hailing from Stockton (holla!) Dean's been
> rocking dance 
> floors since 1996 with some raw tracks you ain't never
> heard! With too 
> many notable gigs to list, let's just say he's been
> doin' this since 
> HomeBase was a Nu-skool spot, ya heard!?!?
> 
> So that's what to expect!  Hope to have you listening!
> 
> 
> -- 
> San Francisco Bay Guardian's Readers Choice Award
> Winner: Best Radio DJ:
> http://www.sfbg.com/promo/pollpositions.php
> AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)
> 
> "Opinions are my own only, and do not necessarily
> represent those of
> KZSU Radio or Stanford University." (or words to that
> effect.)
>

> For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org
> 
> ---------------------------------------------------------------------
> To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
> For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org
